{"term":"1956","caseName":"Securities and Exchange Commission v. Louisiana Public Service Commission","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1956/466","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - May 01, 1957","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13279","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":0,"stop":13.276,"duration":13.28},{"text":"On yesterday, may it please the Court, we considered and sketched briefly the Louisiana Public Service Commission, its powers, its duties and its obligations and compared them on parallel courses as far as practical with the functions of the S. E. C.","start":13.276,"stop":34.359,"duration":21.08},{"text":"We also discussed the right of judicial review of any order made under subsection 11 of the Public Utility Holding Company Act.","start":34.359,"stop":45.77,"duration":11.41},{"text":"Today, I should like to discuss the merits of the case with particular reference to the Louisiana Public Service Commission, applying the principles of Section 11, subsection 1 (a), (b) and (c) of the Act because we feel that the objectives, the obligations and duties of that Commission do not conflict with those of the S. E. C.","start":45.77,"stop":83.953,"duration":38.18},{"text":"That their orbits of influence need not necessarily clash, that the Congress when it enacted the Public Utility Holding Company Act and particularly when it inserted the proviso which I shall read in a moment in Section 11 (b) (1), that it intended to take care of a situation exactly such as we described on the merits of this case.","start":83.953,"stop":110.693,"duration":26.74},{"text":"And so it is our feeling that a reasonable interpretation of the provisions of the Act would bring the same conclusion here, we hope, that the Fifth Circuit thought was justified under the provisions of the Act.","start":110.693,"stop":132.826,"duration":22.13}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, that to get change in circumstances, it relates to circumstances justified on the basis of circumstances would be in existence prior to the time to the Commission's original order?","start":132.826,"stop":150.422,"duration":17.6}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Or at the time of the Commission's original order and subsequent thereto.","start":150.422,"stop":153.756,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there are two things indifferent (Inaudible)","start":153.756,"stop":156.304,"duration":2.55}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":156.304,"stop":156.748,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But you do -- you do (Inaudible) I take it to support the Fifth Circuit (Voice Overlap) --","start":156.748,"stop":163.031,"duration":6.28}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I do but I don't find it entirely necessary to do so.","start":163.031,"stop":166.657,"duration":3.63},{"text":"Yes, I do -- I made the point to the Fifth Circuit and they agreed with the point which we raised, but I find that there has been and we have alleged a change of circumstances.","start":166.657,"stop":182.521,"duration":15.86},{"text":"You can take it on either premise if you will.","start":182.521,"stop":184.417,"duration":1.9},{"text":"If you feel that the circumstances at the time based on the erroneous legal interpretations as such that the S. E. C. has committed error, you could find on that basis or if you felt that the facts and circumstances which have occurred subsequent to the earlier order was such that it required a reversal.","start":184.417,"stop":201.294,"duration":16.88},{"text":"You could do it on either point.","start":201.294,"stop":202.734,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there might be a different position (Inaudible) change of circumstances with subsequent change of circumstances that such an order was appealable and after I would suppose it might be doing that, was it not?","start":202.734,"stop":216.752,"duration":14.02}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's -- we have nothing in mind except to remand on any set of circumstances.","start":216.752,"stop":221.664,"duration":4.91},{"text":"We don't ask this Court to decide the case.","start":221.664,"stop":224.991,"duration":3.33},{"text":"The Fifth Circuit remanded the case to the S. E. C. and directed the S. E. C. to try it on the basis of the legal interpretations which it had given.","start":224.991,"stop":234.069,"duration":9.08},{"text":"So we -- one of the points I intend to raise here today, the Louisiana Commission seeks to cooperate with the S. E. C., the Louisiana Commission seeks to work with the S. E. C. on this particular proposition.","start":234.069,"stop":248.449,"duration":14.38},{"text":"It feels it has some peculiar knowledge and information about this particular utility that gives it a better opportunity to regulate it.","start":248.449,"stop":258.029,"duration":9.58},{"text":"As a matter of fact, the S. E. C. can't regulate it beyond whether or not it fits into a -- a holding company system.","start":258.029,"stop":264.845,"duration":6.82},{"text":"The Louisiana --","start":264.845,"stop":264.947,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr -- Mr. Ainsworth, on the question of finality of the S. E. C. order.","start":264.947,"stop":271.017,"duration":6.07},{"text":"How long after the time for appeal has expired, would you say that your Commission in these circumstances would have the right to -- to have the case reopened?","start":271.017,"stop":282.724,"duration":11.71}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if your --","start":282.724,"stop":283.383,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"This is 19 months after the time for appeal --","start":283.383,"stop":286.088,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":286.088,"stop":286.15,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- has expired as I recall.","start":286.15,"stop":287.498,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":287.498,"stop":288.645,"duration":1.15},{"text":"The Act doesn't put any particular limitation you -- as I see it, you have to go to the provisions of the Act which allow you the petition for revocation and modification that you are able to state, the conditions upon which the order was predicated do not exist.","start":288.645,"stop":303.667,"duration":15.02}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Would --","start":303.667,"stop":303.766,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, --","start":303.766,"stop":303.91,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that lead you to the conclusion that there is no finality to this order of the S. E. C.?","start":303.91,"stop":309.883,"duration":5.97}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No -- no, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":309.883,"stop":313.169,"duration":3.29},{"text":"The 11 (b) orders must be carried out within one year after they are -- are issued by the S. E. C., unless the S. E. C. extends them and then they may only extend them for one year and we don't have a proposition where for an indefinite period the -- the utility is allowed to fail to comply, it must comply within that particular time limit.","start":313.169,"stop":336.684,"duration":23.52},{"text":"Now, we have petitioned for revocation or modification using the words of the statute and we think allegations which -- which fit within the statute and ask for a revocation or modification before the 11 (b) order has actually gone into effect.","start":336.684,"stop":353.542,"duration":16.86}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, does the -- does the Section that you rely on say that you may petition?","start":353.542,"stop":360.018,"duration":6.48}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, may I --","start":360.018,"stop":360.26,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Or a modification?","start":360.26,"stop":361.21,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"May I read it, sir?","start":361.21,"stop":362.303,"duration":1.09},{"text":"It's (Voice Overlap) --","start":362.303,"stop":362.678,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, (Voice Overlap)","start":362.678,"stop":364.104,"duration":1.43},{"text":"The language as you --","start":364.104,"stop":365.857,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The Section follows -- it's the Section 11 (b) (1) -- it's Section 11 (b) as it is indented in the --","start":365.857,"stop":376.603,"duration":10.75}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":376.603,"stop":376.777,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- copy of the Act which I have.","start":376.777,"stop":378.252,"duration":1.48},{"text":"It's actually the last two sentences of Section 11 (b), \"The Commission may by order revoke or modify any order previously made under this subsection, if, after notice and opportunity for hearing, it finds that the conditions upon which the order was predicated do not exist.\"","start":378.252,"stop":398.716,"duration":20.46},{"text":"Followed immediately behind that is the sentence, \"Any order made under this subsection shall be subject to -- to judicial review as provided in Section 24.\"","start":398.716,"stop":409.906,"duration":11.19}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well now, do you find definite authority in that Section for saying that anybody who has an interest in the matter may -- may apply to the Commission for an order to revoke or modify its original order regardless of the time that -- for appeal?","start":409.906,"stop":427.071,"duration":17.17}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Chief Justice, I won't say anybody because I am not -- I don't know whether it be proper to say so.","start":427.071,"stop":432.794,"duration":5.72},{"text":"I will say that a State Commission under the peculiar circumstances here, where we were asked to submit an offer of proof, where we submitted an elaborate offer of proof which we think would prove the situation, where we allege that the -- that there are erroneous legal interpretations which supported the Commission's later order, that under the circumstances here you must determine whether you think there has been an abuse of the Commission's discretion.","start":432.794,"stop":459.888,"duration":27.09},{"text":"So I say that I would rather pitch my case on the facts of my case rather than to make the broad generality that any person that come in.","start":459.888,"stop":467.239,"duration":7.35},{"text":"I can only apply it to Louisiana Commission, the state regulatory commission which has come in under the peculiar circumstances here and submitted all of its information, had a very lengthy argument before the S. E. C. in consideration of those premises.","start":467.239,"stop":483.544,"duration":16.31},{"text":"And based again on what the Fifth Circuit held to be and which we think in reason and in logic would support the view that they were erroneous legal interpretations, it remanded it for consideration consistent with those legal interpretations.","start":483.544,"stop":499.1,"duration":15.56},{"text":"I don't know whether I answered your question or not, sir, but that's -- that's the best (Inaudible) that I can deal with it.","start":499.1,"stop":503.788,"duration":4.69}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it -- in all events it's your answer but it -- it seems to me that you put a burden on the S. E. C. because they were responsive enough to your telegram to say, well, on what grounds do you -- do you believe that this order should -- should be modified?","start":503.788,"stop":524.735,"duration":20.95},{"text":"It seems to me that that -- that that isn't the same as -- as the Commission initiating a request to your Commission to go out and investigate this thing and --","start":524.735,"stop":539.147,"duration":14.41}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I admit that.","start":539.147,"stop":539.993,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and ask them to do something about it.","start":539.993,"stop":542.46,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I must concede that Your Honor is right about that.","start":542.46,"stop":544.998,"duration":2.54},{"text":"The S. E. C. did not initiate this petition, we did initiate it.","start":544.998,"stop":548.502,"duration":3.5},{"text":"The S. E. C. gave sufficient deference to the Louisiana Commission and to say, what is the basis upon which you would care to come in here --","start":548.502,"stop":556.176,"duration":7.67}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":556.176,"stop":556.605,"duration":0.43},{"text":"I --","start":556.605,"stop":556.702,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I did --","start":556.702,"stop":556.93,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- think that's --","start":556.93,"stop":557.155,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- did so.","start":557.155,"stop":557.686,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- about all we (Voice Overlap) --","start":557.686,"stop":558.268,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't attempt to say that the S. E. C. initiated the investigation because I assume that they were content with their order, they still are with there March 20th, 1953 order.","start":558.268,"stop":568.51,"duration":10.24},{"text":"But I say that you must examine the facts of this case and see whether or not you think there has been an abuse of discretion particularly where we hold with the Fifth Circuit that the conclusions were based on -- on erroneous legal interpretations.","start":568.51,"stop":582.84,"duration":14.33},{"text":"And if you would apply those erroneous legal interpretations, we say you couldn't make out a case under the provisions of this Act because the Commission has so narrowly construed the Clause (a) provisions of the subsection that it would be impossible to do so.","start":582.84,"stop":598.331,"duration":15.49},{"text":"If I may, I would like to develop briefly the offer of proof.Before doing so may I point out that the proviso which I promised I would read that and I haven't done so and I would like just to sketch the proviso for a moment.","start":598.331,"stop":616.882,"duration":18.55},{"text":"Section --","start":616.882,"stop":616.931,"duration":0.05}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is that, Mr. --","start":616.931,"stop":618.036,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's in the pamphlet, part of the Act which the S. E. C. gave you in the blue bound copy.","start":618.036,"stop":625.688,"duration":7.65},{"text":"It's the first document, I believe.","start":625.688,"stop":628.206,"duration":2.52},{"text":"Yes, Mr. Meeker points out that it is and the first -- it's the first --","start":628.206,"stop":633.379,"duration":5.17}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh -- oh, yes.","start":633.379,"stop":633.638,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- pamphlet here.","start":633.638,"stop":634.68,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":634.68,"stop":635.228,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It's on page 20 of that pamphlet.","start":635.228,"stop":645.239,"duration":10.01},{"text":"Section 11 (b), I will paraphrase or not repeat all of the words of the first subsection 1, but when I get the proviso, I'll read every word that it shall be the duty of the Commission to require by order that each registered holding company shall take such action as the Commission shall find necessary to limit its operations to a single integrated public utility system.\"","start":645.239,"stop":671.87,"duration":26.63},{"text":"Now, provided -- I have skipped several words there, but I don't think they're pertinent particularly, provided, however, that the Commission shall permit a registered holding company to continue to control one or more additional integrated public utility systems if after notice and opportunity to -- for a hearing it finds that (a), each of such additional systems cannot be operated as an independent system without the loss of substantial economies which can be secured by the retention of control by such holding company of such system.","start":671.87,"stop":712.553,"duration":40.68},{"text":"And then the (b) and (c) provisions, I don't believe are -- are at issue here but they are interesting to see whether or not we are -- we fit with them and (b) states that all of such additional systems are located in one state or in an adjoining states or in a contiguous foreign country.","start":712.553,"stop":729.181,"duration":16.63},{"text":"The Louisiana Power System is entirely located within the State of Louisiana.","start":729.181,"stop":733.499,"duration":4.32},{"text":"The (c) provision states that the contingent combination of such systems under the control of the holding company, I skipped a few words, is not so large as to impair the advantages of localized management, efficient operation or the effectiveness of regulation.","start":733.499,"stop":749.479,"duration":15.98},{"text":"Now, may it please the Court, the proviso in the Act somewhat softened the impact of the directive to the S. E. C. which Congress had passed in this particular Act and there was a reason for that, there had been a disagreement.","start":749.479,"stop":768.433,"duration":18.95},{"text":"The legislative history shows there had been a disagreement between the Senate and the House as to what the provisions of the Act should be.","start":768.433,"stop":778.017,"duration":9.58},{"text":"The Senate passed a version.","start":778.017,"stop":779.356,"duration":1.34},{"text":"The House passed a version with amendments.","start":779.356,"stop":782.226,"duration":2.87},{"text":"The amendments were not concurred in by the Senate and it was necessary that the matter go to conference.","start":782.226,"stop":787.823,"duration":5.6},{"text":"And after the conference, there was an attempt made in the House to adopt the Conference Report which in effect would adopt the Senate bill which did not have this proviso.","start":787.823,"stop":797.144,"duration":9.32},{"text":"That -- the House rejected the agreement to -- to the Conference Report and another Conference Report was prepared which contains the provisions which are now in the Act and which we are adopted.","start":797.144,"stop":808.752,"duration":11.61},{"text":"Now, the Conference Report of the House, which I find on page 20 of the Louisiana Power's brief and I will borrow that paragraph from their brief makes this significant statement, \"The conference substitute meets the House's desire to provide for a further flexibility by the statement of additional definite and concrete circumstances under which exception should be made to the form of one integrated system.\"","start":808.752,"stop":838.089,"duration":29.34},{"text":"I ask Your Honors to note the word “flexibility” and that was what the proviso was designed to do and that's what we think it did do.","start":838.089,"stop":846.516,"duration":8.43},{"text":"“Definite exceptions not only provide a satisfactory constitutional standard but also an effective standard for the guidance of both the Securities and Exchange Commission and those holding companies which wished voluntary -- voluntarily to comply with congressional policy.”","start":846.516,"stop":864.401,"duration":17.88},{"text":"It's the end of the quotation.","start":864.401,"stop":867.116,"duration":2.72},{"text":"So we -- we think that the proviso as a matter of fact one of the Circuit Judges said, I think, perhaps on a dissenting opinion that the Act would not have passed had the proviso not been inserted in it.","start":867.116,"stop":881.392,"duration":14.28},{"text":"And I think we may imply that from the legislative history because of the failure of the first Conference Report, they have been concurred in by the House of Representatives.","start":881.392,"stop":890.105,"duration":8.71},{"text":"So I think we may fairly say that this Public Utility Holding Company Act would not have passed had this proviso not been inserted in it.","start":890.105,"stop":898.477,"duration":8.37},{"text":"Now, in --","start":898.477,"stop":899.065,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Ainsworth, is it subject also to -- might it be subject to the interpretation that Congress says, “Well now, even after making an order which has become final, the Commission may, in its discretion by order, revoke or modify that order but if it does, anyone who is injured by that action on its part shall have the right of judicial review.”","start":899.065,"stop":930.804,"duration":31.74}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It's susceptible to that construction and I think it is (Voice Overlap) --","start":930.804,"stop":932.865,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is that -- is that an unreasonable construction?","start":932.865,"stop":935.502,"duration":2.64}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't think it's unreasonable but I again say that I'm not seeking that interpretation here.","start":935.502,"stop":940.806,"duration":5.3},{"text":"I ask only -- and I'm not trying to be illogical about it, I ask only that -- that this Court hold under these particular facts and circumstances and this particular State Commission coming here whether it is entitled any greater consideration or not is something that I am not prepared to say.","start":940.806,"stop":958.022,"duration":17.22},{"text":"But I have in sketching the background of the Act upon yesterday, attempted to show Your Honors that Congress in passing the Act felt that -- that the word of the State Commission under certain circumstances was very vital.","start":958.022,"stop":972.197,"duration":14.17},{"text":"In fact, they wouldn't give approval of certain types of transactions without State Commission approval.","start":972.197,"stop":977.733,"duration":5.54},{"text":"Now, that is purely an analogy, I agree and I'm just trying to -- to bring it by analogy but for any person, Mr. Chief Justice, I wouldn't -- I say it's susceptible to that construction but I don't ask for it here, I ask only that you hold that this Commission can come in and do so.","start":977.733,"stop":998.033,"duration":20.3},{"text":"Now, the offer of proof which the Louisiana Commission filed stated that it had exercised jurisdiction over the retail electric and gas rates of this company of -- for residential, commercial and so forth uses that the Commission requires Louisiana Power to file annual reports that it had fixed the electric rate base of Louisiana Power back in 1946, had prescribed its allowable rate of return, that its electric -- at Louisiana Power's electric accounts are classified on the uniform systems of accounts as or the gas accounts.","start":998.033,"stop":1037.127,"duration":39.09},{"text":"And then in the offer of proof, Louisiana Commission used the language of the (a), (b), (c) provisions of the proviso which I have just read and alleged that the facts would say -- would show in the offer of proof, fitted into those particular provisions.","start":1037.127,"stop":1052.872,"duration":15.75},{"text":"And it said that there is no law of the State of Louisiana which prohibits the ownership by utility of both an electric and gas system.","start":1052.872,"stop":1060.905,"duration":8.03},{"text":"That Louisiana Power has the express approval of the Louisiana Commission to have both an electric and gas system.","start":1060.905,"stop":1068.358,"duration":7.45},{"text":"That the public interest would best be served by the continued operation of Louisiana Power of both in electric and gas system and it supported that by a letter from the Governor of the State and by letters from the officials of 28 of the 30 towns and cities which this company serves and 14 of the 15 parishes or counties which are involved in this particular system, which are covered and embraced in this particular system.","start":1068.358,"stop":1098.54,"duration":30.18},{"text":"It further supported its offer of proof by a separation study, a detail separation study which you will find in the record at pages -- beginning at page 16.","start":1098.54,"stop":1110.284,"duration":11.74},{"text":"And it showed that the total additional cost to consumers and customers of Louisiana Power would be $957,000 a year of which $684,000 would be lost to the electric system and $272,000 would be lost to the gas system.","start":1110.284,"stop":1130.214,"duration":19.93},{"text":"The separation study was -- was made by taking the operations of this company for 1954 and extracting from the electric system of accounts all charges that had heretofore the -- extracting from the books, I'd better say.","start":1130.214,"stop":1146.578,"duration":16.36},{"text":"Those charges which had heretofore been made for the gas system and set -- setting up and projecting two separate corporations just as if they had operated separately on that particular year.","start":1146.578,"stop":1156.548,"duration":9.97},{"text":"And it was natural that there should be and the -- the loss of $957,000 came from the fact that you were going to have two overhead cost where you had one before.","start":1156.548,"stop":1169.614,"duration":13.07},{"text":"And because of the fact that this particular company's gas, customers are largely also its electric customers there's going to be a duplication of activity, duplication of billing, of reading the meters, of -- duplication of administrative officers and so forth.","start":1169.614,"stop":1184.119,"duration":14.5},{"text":"And the total that's shown in the record here, the exact amount is actually computed by the Louisiana Commission's own staff and it comes out to what Louisiana Commission considered a very large sum of money which would be lost to customers of Louisiana Power by divestiture of the gas system in a separation of the gas system from the electric system.","start":1184.119,"stop":1202.776,"duration":18.66}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Ainsworth, is there anything in the record which would indicate why the utility itself did not take an appeal or was not the moving party in this situation?","start":1202.776,"stop":1214.718,"duration":11.94}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1214.718,"stop":1215.242,"duration":0.52},{"text":"I -- and I -- I'm not prepared to say.","start":1215.242,"stop":1218.117,"duration":2.88},{"text":"I don't -- there is nothing in the record on that subject.","start":1218.117,"stop":1223.109,"duration":4.99},{"text":"Now, another thing that was brought in the offer of proof was that under the peculiar facts and circumstances and based somewhat upon the climatic conditions of the State of Louisiana that been -- that the gas and electric systems tended to compliment each other, that in the summer you had a higher use of electricity, in the winter you had a higher use of gas.","start":1223.109,"stop":1243.442,"duration":20.33},{"text":"And there's an exhibit in this record that shows that by combining the two on six months basis beginning in November through April and from May through October that they balanced out the total revenues from the two systems, averaged out about 50% each time.","start":1243.442,"stop":1259.506,"duration":16.06},{"text":"So that the company, by virtue of having the two systems, tended to have a complete operation from the very nature of things inherent in the operation of the company.","start":1259.506,"stop":1269.658,"duration":10.15},{"text":"Louisiana Commission said that it -- in it's offer of proof that it had -- had long experience with this utility, that it believed it to be an efficient operation, that it had found its regulation in Louisiana Power to be most effective that that company had never had been given a rate increase.","start":1269.658,"stop":1289.533,"duration":19.88},{"text":"On the other hand, it had given electric rate reductions that the only gas increase that had ever occurred was one equal to the amount of the increase in the wholesale cost of gas to this particular company.","start":1289.533,"stop":1302.019,"duration":12.49},{"text":"And so, on the basis and on the predicate of -- and I have skimmed through it only very briefly, they held the Louisiana Commission felt that the facts justified a holding that giving a reasonable interpretation to the Section 11 (b) (1), particular Clause (a), that the loss of economies was a substantial one, the Courts have held that substantial means important economies.","start":1302.019,"stop":1331.137,"duration":29.12},{"text":"That's the Circuit -- the Second Circuit held that, the Fifth Circuit held it in our own case.","start":1331.137,"stop":1336.32,"duration":5.18},{"text":"We say substantial is a relative and an elastic term.","start":1336.32,"stop":1340.319,"duration":4},{"text":"The S. E. C. interprets substantial to mean that the losses must be so great that the severed system, here the gas system, could not continue to operate independently, economically.","start":1340.319,"stop":1351.746,"duration":11.43},{"text":"Now, we say that that conclusion is simply not justified by the language of the statute and that is an erroneous interpretation and it -- it confines this proviso so tight that it would be practically impossible to fit within it.","start":1351.746,"stop":1367.689,"duration":15.94},{"text":"In other words, that it has the effect of nullifying the proviso.","start":1367.689,"stop":1371.304,"duration":3.62},{"text":"We also say that the loss of substantial economies should relate not only to the severed system, the gas system, but also to the principal system, the electric system, that it would be blinding one's eyes to reality as the brief of the Louisiana Commission says when it -- which was submitted to the S. E. C.","start":1371.304,"stop":1389.826,"duration":18.52},{"text":"You did not take the total loss into consideration.","start":1389.826,"stop":1392.557,"duration":2.73}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But aren't all of those arguments, matters which had you appeared in the original proceedings you would have addressed to the Commission.","start":1392.557,"stop":1400.996,"duration":8.44},{"text":"And what -- I haven't heard anything that you said that supports this allegation in your supplemental petition where you allege that since the -- subsequent to the issuance of the order herein there have occurred substantial and important changes in the condition and so forth.","start":1400.996,"stop":1417.203,"duration":16.21}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, actually, may it please the Court, there are a number of things shown in the offer of proof whether you consider them substantial changes in circumstances.","start":1417.203,"stop":1426.487,"duration":9.28},{"text":"That's why a moment ago when you asked me the question, I didn't want to confine it only to that, I also feel that we have to go back to the conditions that existed at the time the original order was issued which were based upon erroneous legal interpretations.","start":1426.487,"stop":1438.317,"duration":11.83},{"text":"But to answer your question more directly, the order was issued in 1953, the early order, the separation study was based on facts and circumstances in 1954.","start":1438.317,"stop":1449.994,"duration":11.68},{"text":"Since the order of 1953 had been issued, it had been possible to find out that the -- the severed or gas system would have to pay a larger amount for a debt service because Louisiana Power had actually gone into the market and sought that financing for the company that was to be set up to take over the gas system.","start":1449.994,"stop":1467.862,"duration":17.87},{"text":"That in addition to that the Louisiana Commission had the benefit of the studies of the operations of the Arkansas Power & Light Company and the Mississippi Power & Light Company which has severed their gas systems to show what the increase cost had been to those companies or no longer being able to allocate part of their overhead expenses to gas system.","start":1467.862,"stop":1488.629,"duration":20.77},{"text":"And the -- the running of time was necessary in order to have that information before the Commission, it could not have been obtained, it could not have been submitted to the S. E. C. at the time because those systems had only then been severed and it -- the information wasn't then available.","start":1488.629,"stop":1503.235,"duration":14.61},{"text":"So we put it on two premises as the Fifth Circuit said that it could -- that the Court could examine the conditions that truly prevailed at the time the original order was made.","start":1503.235,"stop":1516.808,"duration":13.57},{"text":"We ask Your Honors to consider these legal interpretations which the S. E. C. has given, which we respectfully suggest are erroneous.","start":1516.808,"stop":1524.542,"duration":7.73},{"text":"We ask you also to examine the offer of proof and decide whether or not in your exercise of judicial authority and discretion, whether or not the facts and circumstances which were shown subsequent to the time of the March 20, 1953 order justify the allegation which you find in the supplemental petition.","start":1524.542,"stop":1542.703,"duration":18.16},{"text":"That's our case, we stand or fall on it, if Your Honors please.","start":1542.703,"stop":1546.77,"duration":4.07},{"text":"And we are anxious that the Louisiana Commission to have the opportunity of cooperating and working with the S. E. C., but we can see no compensating advantages which accrue from the separation of this gas system in Louisiana, it's contrary to the state policy and we feel that if haven't -- if -- if given the opportunity on a remand to go back to the S. E. C., we would hope to persuade our brothers there.","start":1546.77,"stop":1571.693,"duration":24.92},{"text":"Thank you.","start":1571.693,"stop":1581.894,"duration":10.2}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Monroe?","start":1581.894,"stop":1583.642,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1583.642,"stop":1585.3,"duration":1.66},{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":1585.3,"stop":1589.831,"duration":4.53},{"text":"The issues in this case are principally between two -- the two commissions, the Louisiana Commission and the Securities and Exchange Commission.","start":1589.831,"stop":1599.454,"duration":9.62},{"text":"My client file -- finds itself very much in the position of a patient being operated on by two doctors, each with a different diagnosis.","start":1599.454,"stop":1612.58,"duration":13.13},{"text":"So I would like to say a few words from the way point of view of the patient.","start":1612.58,"stop":1619.333,"duration":6.75},{"text":"First, to clear up a question that was raised --","start":1619.333,"stop":1622.296,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"If the patient -- why didn't the patient object an appeal from the first operation?","start":1622.296,"stop":1629.636,"duration":7.34}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"If Your Honor please.","start":1629.636,"stop":1630.919,"duration":1.28},{"text":"The patient appeared at the original hearing in 1953 and sincerely believing that the gas and electric systems could not be operated separately without the loss of substantial economies.","start":1630.919,"stop":1647.021,"duration":16.1},{"text":"Introduced documentary and oral testimony which purported to show savings of approximately $450,000, I mean increased cost of that amount in the electric properties in the separate operation and about $250,000 in the gas properties.","start":1647.021,"stop":1669.857,"duration":22.84},{"text":"The S. E. C. held that that was not a showing of a sufficient -- of a loss of substantial economies sufficient to make the conditions.","start":1669.857,"stop":1681.844,"duration":11.99},{"text":"We felt at -- at that time at -- on the basis of the record and without the official nonpartisan findings of a Commission or with that or -- and also there not having been a complete separation study made that our chances on appeal were not very good.","start":1681.844,"stop":1704.118,"duration":22.27},{"text":"And that's the reason we did not appeal.","start":1704.118,"stop":1706.514,"duration":2.4},{"text":"But we sincerely believe that we are right in the position that we took and we felt perhaps we had not made a sufficiently good record.","start":1706.514,"stop":1717.514,"duration":11}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you make any effort at the time to have the Louisiana Commission come in?","start":1717.514,"stop":1724.419,"duration":6.91}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"No, we did not, Your Honor.","start":1724.419,"stop":1726.385,"duration":1.97},{"text":"We were before the Securities and Exchange Commission and not before the Louisiana Commission.","start":1726.385,"stop":1733.642,"duration":7.26},{"text":"Now, at that time there was no outstanding order which the Louisiana Commission later entered.","start":1733.642,"stop":1742.044,"duration":8.4},{"text":"In June the 16th, 1953, the Louisiana Commission entered a general order that no disposition of properties could be made by any utility under its jurisdiction without its permission and if -- if that general order had been in effect we probably would've sought to get them to come in and state their position at that time but that order was only entered later.","start":1742.044,"stop":1767.101,"duration":25.06}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Monroe, was not the Securities and Exchange Commission the proper place to make this factual showing that you've just related?","start":1767.101,"stop":1778.577,"duration":11.48}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, we did -- we did endeavor --","start":1778.577,"stop":1780.369,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"And --","start":1780.369,"stop":1780.555,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to make that factual.","start":1780.555,"stop":1781.4,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and they had jurisdiction to determine the controversy, did they not?","start":1781.4,"stop":1787.543,"duration":6.14}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes.","start":1787.543,"stop":1788.053,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"And they did determine it, did they not?","start":1788.053,"stop":1790.13,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes.","start":1790.13,"stop":1790.889,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"You had a certain time within which to appeal, did you not?","start":1790.889,"stop":1794.268,"duration":3.38}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1794.268,"stop":1794.877,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"No appeal was taken.","start":1794.877,"stop":1796.916,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1796.916,"stop":1797.424,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, then is it your argument that the Louisiana Commission, a year-and-a-half later can come to this proceeding on a motion to reopen and without showing change of condition and limit itself to those changes of condition, have a rehearing of the matter heard and determined by the Commission a year-and-a-half before?","start":1797.424,"stop":1829.203,"duration":31.78}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Whittaker, that is a -- an argument of the Commission -- of the Louisiana Commission.","start":1829.203,"stop":1838.475,"duration":9.27},{"text":"We have simply confined ourselves to an argument of the substantive questions here but because we -- we failed to appeal, however, we -- we do believe that until the Act that the order of the Commission is carried out.","start":1838.475,"stop":1858.225,"duration":19.75},{"text":"In other words, until the -- the death sentence is executed then a body such as the Louisiana Commission, which is primarily concerned with the regulation of the rights of Louisiana, should be allowed to come in and to show, one, that the -- that the order of the Commission was based on erroneous interpretations of law.","start":1858.225,"stop":1882.418,"duration":24.19}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, that it was wrong?","start":1882.418,"stop":1884.437,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1884.437,"stop":1885.32,"duration":0.88},{"text":"That it was wrong --","start":1885.32,"stop":1885.729,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Even though findings?","start":1885.729,"stop":1888.187,"duration":2.46}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"That it -- that the -- the interpretations of law were wrong and all -- and that -- that they were so wrong that they within themselves constitute a change of convictions.","start":1888.187,"stop":1899.97,"duration":11.78},{"text":"And I say to Your Honor also the fact that -- that the Public Service Commission and the -- the governing bodies of all the -- of all but one of the parishes in which we operate and the -- and all the municipalities, all of them gave expression that it was against the public interest to sever these properties is a new fact which should be taken into consideration when entering this severance order.","start":1899.97,"stop":1930.406,"duration":30.44}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Your claim -- your claim is wholly derivative.","start":1930.406,"stop":1933.597,"duration":3.19},{"text":"You impress whatever claim you press merely if the Louisiana Commission has standards.","start":1933.597,"stop":1939.85,"duration":6.25}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1939.85,"stop":1940.448,"duration":0.6},{"text":"We -- we are -- we are really here just arguing the substantive question (Voice Overlap) --","start":1940.448,"stop":1944.905,"duration":4.46}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That was not about that can bring you in if you can come in.","start":1944.905,"stop":1947.874,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":1947.874,"stop":1948.355,"duration":0.48},{"text":"I've been brought here.","start":1948.355,"stop":1949.217,"duration":0.86},{"text":"[Laughs]","start":1949.217,"stop":1950.892,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what are the conditions that are so changed now as to make you think that these findings of the Commission, the S. E. C. Commission are so erroneous that this Court should take judicial notice of it and -- and permit the reopening, when at the time your -- your minds were charged with it and you had just had the hearing, you were of the opinion that they -- they were so close to being right that you didn't think you had any chance of appeal?","start":1950.892,"stop":1984.281,"duration":33.39}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as -- let me answer you in two stages.","start":1984.281,"stop":1990.349,"duration":6.07},{"text":"First; we don't think that you are limited to showing a change of conditions, as the statue says you simply are showing that the conditions upon which said order do not exist.","start":1990.349,"stop":2003.621,"duration":13.27},{"text":"And we say that the -- one of the conditions on which the order were issued were erroneous interpretations of a meaning of -- of proviso (a) -- Section 11 (a) (Voice Overlap) --","start":2003.621,"stop":2016.593,"duration":12.97}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"It seems to me that -- it seems to me that makes the question more pertinent even and as I stated if -- if they were so near right at the time they were made that you felt that there was no chance of you -- of you getting a review of the case.","start":2016.593,"stop":2036.687,"duration":20.09},{"text":"Why do you now think that those --","start":2036.687,"stop":2038.287,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":2038.287,"stop":2038.348,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- same findings based --","start":2038.348,"stop":2039.374,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":2039.374,"stop":2039.56,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- upon those same conditions are so wrong that this Court should take judicial notice of it and upset the whole procedure and -- and go into it again?","start":2039.56,"stop":2048.983,"duration":9.42}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":2048.983,"stop":2049.693,"duration":0.71},{"text":"I'd like to answer that question, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":2049.693,"stop":2052.585,"duration":2.89},{"text":"At the time in 1953, in examining the -- the decisions of the Courts of Appeal, we found certain dicta from -- in at least two cases which would indicate that the interpretations of the S. E. C. might be upheld.","start":2052.585,"stop":2071.043,"duration":18.46},{"text":"They were the Engineers Public Service case and the Philadelphia case.","start":2071.043,"stop":2078.759,"duration":7.72},{"text":"Since that time, you have another decision directly in point by the Fifth Circuit court below and so --","start":2078.759,"stop":2088.411,"duration":9.65}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"In this case?","start":2088.411,"stop":2089.315,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"In this case it, directly on these points and so I say there is a different situation here.","start":2089.315,"stop":2096.414,"duration":7.1},{"text":"When we were considering appeal, we were considering the state of the law and then -- and we were also considering state of our record.","start":2096.414,"stop":2104.993,"duration":8.58},{"text":"Now, you asked about the changed conditions, as I said, I think the fact that an examination into whether the public interest would be served by this and -- and that's one of the standards by which the Act should be interpreted.","start":2104.993,"stop":2122.542,"duration":17.55},{"text":"That has been more or less determined by a -- a careful examination of it by the Louisiana Public Service and the impartial body and also by expressions from the -- from the governing authorities of the parishes and cities where this gas system operates and -- does that answer your question, Mr. Chief Justice?","start":2122.542,"stop":2147.003,"duration":24.46}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's -- it's your answer that's --","start":2147.003,"stop":2148.898,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"[Laughter]","start":2148.898,"stop":2152.416,"duration":3.52},{"text":"Well, as I said, our point of view is one that we -- we do not have to show changed conditions, that number two that there are -- there are changes.","start":2152.416,"stop":2164.853,"duration":12.44}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't have to, meaning you can't if you were here alone without the (Voice Overlap) --","start":2164.853,"stop":2170.582,"duration":5.73}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no --","start":2170.582,"stop":2170.913,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- you wouldn't be here.","start":2170.913,"stop":2172.235,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"I should not be making this argument --","start":2172.235,"stop":2173.518,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":2173.518,"stop":2173.981,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Mr. --","start":2173.981,"stop":2174.45,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the point.","start":2174.45,"stop":2174.695,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to the Chief Justice.","start":2174.695,"stop":2175.826,"duration":1.13},{"text":"I didn't intend to bring it.","start":2175.826,"stop":2176.888,"duration":1.06},{"text":"[Laughs] But getting back to -- to Louisiana, I want to point out that Louisiana Power & Light Company is an operating company and it's always been an operating company and it operates both the gas and electric systems entirely within the State of Louisiana.","start":2176.888,"stop":2199.27,"duration":22.38},{"text":"Mr. Justice Douglas asked whether it was registered, yesterday.","start":2199.27,"stop":2204.02,"duration":4.75},{"text":"It's not registered because it is not a holding company but it is a subsidiary of a registered holding company and as such is subject to the Act.","start":2204.02,"stop":2213.021,"duration":9},{"text":"Now, and I want to point out too that it -- there is no problem here involved of the use of a holding company device to permit the joint operation of gas and electric properties where it's against the policy of the State.","start":2213.021,"stop":2236.046,"duration":23.02},{"text":"Now, that was one of the considerations in writing the Holding Company Act.","start":2236.046,"stop":2241.164,"duration":5.12},{"text":"Here, always that Louisiana Power & Light has operated both gas and electric properties so there's no -- and in Louisiana, the other comparable electric companies who were not subject to the Holding Company Act also operate gas and the Commission has had experience with this joint operation.","start":2241.164,"stop":2266.016,"duration":24.85},{"text":"Now, we submit, if Your Honor please, that on the state of the record in this case, it must be assumed that if this separation is or complied with that there will be a loss of $957,000, a minimum of that -- a year.","start":2266.016,"stop":2290.198,"duration":24.18},{"text":"That there will be a additional cost to a separated gas properties in the form of a higher interest rate, it was estimated by the Commission at approximately $28,000 a year.","start":2290.198,"stop":2304.489,"duration":14.29},{"text":"Also there will be loss, the other advantages of combined operation.","start":2304.489,"stop":2309.686,"duration":5.2},{"text":"It must also be assumed that there are no compensating advantages of any sort in the natural course of events, this additional cost of operation is bound to be born by the -- the rate payers of Louisiana's gas customers and electric customers.","start":2309.686,"stop":2331.409,"duration":21.72},{"text":"Now, this seems to be admittedly a highly undesirable result and therefore in approaching the interpretation of Section 11 (b) (1) (a), we ask ourselves does that -- do those words require this result?","start":2331.409,"stop":2351.88,"duration":20.47},{"text":"Now, those words which have been quoted by -- by counsel for the Commission are these.","start":2351.88,"stop":2364.65,"duration":12.77},{"text":"The -- in order to retain the system this is the first requirement, each such additional system cannot be operated as an independent system without the loss of substantial economies which can be secured by the retention of control by such holding company of such system.","start":2364.65,"stop":2384.189,"duration":19.54},{"text":"Now, the S. E. C. says that requires this result because you can only take into account the cost to the gas system.","start":2384.189,"stop":2393.955,"duration":9.77}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"The additional system?","start":2393.955,"stop":2395.34,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, to the system that you -- you're severing, can't take into the question of fact that there's a great loss of economy to the -- the remaining system, the electric system.","start":2395.34,"stop":2407.8,"duration":12.46},{"text":"I don't see that anywhere in this -- in the language because the language says the loss of substantial economies which can be secured by retention.","start":2407.8,"stop":2417.316,"duration":9.52},{"text":"Now, it also -- S. E. C. also says, the loss to this system to be severed must be so great that the severed system is incapable of economic operation.","start":2417.316,"stop":2431.562,"duration":14.25},{"text":"Well, that -- that is nowhere in the statute and that is reading the exception into -- reading it practically out of the statute.","start":2431.562,"stop":2441.622,"duration":10.06},{"text":"We submit that in the -- from the ordinary meaning of the words, those interpretations are not justified.","start":2441.622,"stop":2453.852,"duration":12.23},{"text":"We also point out that --","start":2453.852,"stop":2456.803,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- you would read (a) as -- as if it read each of such additional systems cannot be operated as an independent system without the loss of substantial economies to the holding company system?","start":2456.803,"stop":2475.799,"duration":19}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"Loss of substantial economies of any sort.","start":2475.799,"stop":2480.024,"duration":4.22}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"To the holding company system?","start":2480.024,"stop":2481.762,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2481.762,"stop":2482.142,"duration":0.38},{"text":"Well, that's right.","start":2482.142,"stop":2484.268,"duration":2.13},{"text":"This can be secured.","start":2484.268,"stop":2486.103,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"And the S. E. C. reached at this -- each of such additional systems cannot be operated as an independent system without the loss of substantial economies to the additional system.","start":2486.103,"stop":2497.078,"duration":10.97}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"That's one of their interpretations but I -- in order to -- in order to expressly give the meaning that S. E. C. wants to give to this language, you'll have to add 15 words -- 15 words to this Section.","start":2497.078,"stop":2515.158,"duration":18.08},{"text":"There's -- and this Section only has 34.","start":2515.158,"stop":2518.911,"duration":3.75},{"text":"You have to add the words loss of substantial economies “to such independent systems so great as to make them incapable of independent economic operation.”","start":2518.911,"stop":2530.854,"duration":11.94},{"text":"All those words would have to be added for Congress to expressly state that the interpretations of S. E. C. in regard.","start":2530.854,"stop":2540.428,"duration":9.57},{"text":"Now, we point out that the express intent of Congress in -- is in accordance with the ordinary meaning of these words, 70 times in the -- in the statute of the public interest and for the protection of consumers and investors is repeated throughout the statute.","start":2540.428,"stop":2562.832,"duration":22.4},{"text":"And we submit that measuring the facts of this case against the public interest and the interest of consumers is very clear that -- that in -- the interpretation should be in accordance with the actual words of the statute.","start":2562.832,"stop":2581.311,"duration":18.48},{"text":"Also, in Section 1 (c) of the Act, it -- there it -- it is stated as the declared purpose of the Act in accordance with which all the section should be interpreted that this Act is intended to -- to cure certain enumerated evils and if you -- we have printed Section 1 (b) where those evils are enumerated in -- in the appendix to our brief and after careful consideration of them we'll indicate that there's -- there are none of those involved here at all.","start":2581.311,"stop":2616.003,"duration":34.69},{"text":"In the reply brief filed yesterday, the S. E. C. suggested that -- that the Section 11 (b) (4) -- 11 (b) (4) might be here involved.","start":2616.003,"stop":2639.414,"duration":23.41},{"text":"Now, 11 (b) (4) is one of the evils that is when the growth and extension of holding companies bears no relation to economy of management and operation or the integration of coordinated -- coordination of related progress.","start":2639.414,"stop":2657.494,"duration":18.08},{"text":"There is no question here involved of growth or extension.","start":2657.494,"stop":2661.075,"duration":3.58},{"text":"We have had these gas properties since 1927.","start":2661.075,"stop":2665.352,"duration":4.28},{"text":"There's -- there is no question here about integration or coordination.","start":2665.352,"stop":2671.773,"duration":6.42},{"text":"The gas properties are entirely within the electric territory which we said, so that -- that there's no evil in there that would be cured by this order.","start":2671.773,"stop":2684.062,"duration":12.29}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- what do you say to Senator Wheeler's --","start":2684.062,"stop":2688.487,"duration":4.43}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"If Your Honor --","start":2688.487,"stop":2688.919,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- comment on this --","start":2688.919,"stop":2689.905,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2689.905,"stop":2690.483,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- proviso?","start":2690.483,"stop":2691.296,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, if Your Honor please.","start":2691.296,"stop":2693.178,"duration":1.88},{"text":"The history of the enactment of the Act shows that Senator Wheeler's statement was -- stands alone of anything to support this interpretation by the S. E. C.","start":2693.178,"stop":2707.028,"duration":13.85},{"text":"It was made two days after the crucial vote in the House.","start":2707.028,"stop":2712.833,"duration":5.81},{"text":"The House vote -- the crucial vote in the House came on --","start":2712.833,"stop":2715.826,"duration":2.99}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"It was on a -- a report of the -- of the Congress --","start":2715.826,"stop":2718.711,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2718.711,"stop":2719.214,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- wasn't it, to the Senate?","start":2719.214,"stop":2719.838,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"Not -- No.","start":2719.838,"stop":2720.691,"duration":0.85},{"text":"His -- his statement was on the Senate floor after the Senate had passed -- passed it and the Senate had passed the bill earlier that day without objection, had passed the -- agreed to the Conference Report.","start":2720.691,"stop":2738.677,"duration":17.99},{"text":"But two days before -- two days before, the House on a motion to inspect the -- the conferees, to agree to the compromise had -- had voted.","start":2738.677,"stop":2755.172,"duration":16.49},{"text":"That was the crucial thing, the House agreement to the -- so I say that it has no bearing on the interpretation of what this compromise language had meant as far as the House -- what the House was referring to.","start":2755.172,"stop":2769.626,"duration":14.45}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"And I don't suppose there's anyone more important than this legislation that Senator Wheeler unless it was Mr. Rabu?","start":2769.626,"stop":2775.96,"duration":6.33}]},{"speakerName":"J. Raburn Monroe","textObjs":[{"text":"It -- well, if Your Honor please.","start":2775.96,"stop":2777.53,"duration":1.57},{"text":"Senator Wheeler was a strong advocate of the Senate version.","start":2777.53,"stop":2781.778,"duration":4.25},{"text":"He -- he was not an impartial man in this prize at all.","start":2781.778,"stop":2785.696,"duration":3.92},{"text":"He was -- he was advocating no exceptions whatsoever to the one integrated system and it be rather natural that he would intend to interpret it in the narrowest sense.","start":2785.696,"stop":2799.596,"duration":13.9},{"text":"The compromise was known as the (Inaudible) compromise and -- and that -- thank you very much.","start":2799.596,"stop":2810.349,"duration":10.75}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Meeker.","start":2810.349,"stop":2816.718,"duration":6.37}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":2816.718,"stop":2820.47,"duration":3.75},{"text":"With respect to Clause (a) which has been discussed here this morning again, the Commission rests on the interpretation found on page 40 in the Conference Report --","start":2820.47,"stop":2834.125,"duration":13.66}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"40 of your brief?","start":2834.125,"stop":2834.974,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Page 40 of our brief, Mr. Justice Douglas, on the reports of the Conference Committee found right at the top of page 40.","start":2834.974,"stop":2844.843,"duration":9.87},{"text":"We believe that is the substantial legislative history for the interpretation which we have given to the meaning of Clause (a).","start":2844.843,"stop":2857.207,"duration":12.36},{"text":"The respondents have indicated that it cost money to raise money and with that we agree cost money to raise money.","start":2857.207,"stop":2865.512,"duration":8.31},{"text":"In 1953, they didn't bring any evidence in as to the cost of raising money and -- and introduce it before the Commission then and we think it's too late for them to raise that question now.","start":2865.512,"stop":2879.446,"duration":13.93},{"text":"I think it's interesting to note also from the record, page 106, that one commission testified in this 1953 proceeding.","start":2879.446,"stop":2890.03,"duration":10.58},{"text":"A representative of the New Orleans City Commission, Public Utilities Commission, was testified in our 1953 proceeding apparently they had an opportunity to get prepared to appear in that proceeding and did actually so appear and testified, at least a representative of that Commission testified in the support of the company's position in that proceeding.","start":2890.03,"stop":2915.5,"duration":25.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In the history of the death sentence, Mr. Meeker, has there been any -- what has been the experience as to revision of the terms of the sentence before it actually was carried out into execution in time?","start":2915.5,"stop":2933.394,"duration":17.89}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"In terms of modification of --","start":2933.394,"stop":2935.504,"duration":2.11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2935.504,"stop":2935.572,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"-- a prior order --","start":2935.572,"stop":2936.648,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2936.648,"stop":2936.744,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Mr. Justice Frankfurter, there are found in -- in page, I believe it's 16 of our brief.","start":2936.744,"stop":2946.556,"duration":9.81},{"text":"There -- I think I have the wrong -- on page 18 of our brief, Footnote 16, we have collected the cases in which this problem has been before the Commission --","start":2946.556,"stop":2966.538,"duration":19.98}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And what -- what is the tale in the sentences as to --","start":2966.538,"stop":2969.514,"duration":2.98}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't --","start":2969.514,"stop":2969.726,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What is -- what does it -- what does it amount to?","start":2969.726,"stop":2971.315,"duration":1.59},{"text":"What's the experience?","start":2971.315,"stop":2972.735,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"The --","start":2972.735,"stop":2972.825,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It summarizes?","start":2972.825,"stop":2973.606,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"The Commission has in the past modified on application in the showing of change of conditions of prior order.","start":2973.606,"stop":2979.538,"duration":5.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And it -- on its own sua sponte and its own organizations?","start":2979.538,"stop":2984.876,"duration":5.34}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2984.876,"stop":2985.21,"duration":0.33},{"text":"Generally on the application --","start":2985.21,"stop":2986.42,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Generally?","start":2986.42,"stop":2986.907,"duration":0.49},{"text":"Well, I mean at any -- at any --","start":2986.907,"stop":2988.258,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would say I -- I'm not absolutely certain but its my -- my best judgment that it's been almost exclusively on the basis of some application made to the Commission and not on its --","start":2988.258,"stop":2999.182,"duration":10.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It's always --","start":2999.182,"stop":2999.419,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"-- own motion.","start":2999.419,"stop":3000.067,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And always by the potential victims or the prospective victims?","start":3000.067,"stop":3004.389,"duration":4.32}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that's a fair statement.","start":3004.389,"stop":3010.054,"duration":5.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And the time within which those applications were made, have you got any -- laid eyes on that?","start":3010.054,"stop":3018.083,"duration":8.03}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"I would like to submit that to Your Honor, I don't have it in mind at the moment.","start":3018.083,"stop":3021.873,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) or at easy would it be too -- too much of a burden on the Commission because --","start":3021.873,"stop":3026.252,"duration":4.38}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Not at all, Your Honor.","start":3026.252,"stop":3027.188,"duration":0.94},{"text":"I will submit a memorandum promptly.","start":3027.188,"stop":3031.731,"duration":4.54},{"text":"Yesterday, Mr. Chief Justice, you inquired as to the nature of the prior proceedings and I would just like to point out at this time that it was in February of 1940 that the Commission instituted the 11 (b) (1) proceedings against Electric Bond and Share as has been mentioned by respondents counsel here today, including Louisiana which then was a subsidiary of Electric Power & Light Corporation which at that time was a subholding company of Electric Bond and Share.","start":3031.731,"stop":3064.954,"duration":33.22},{"text":"And its interesting to note also that Electric Power & Light became registered a day after this Court's decision in 1938 which sustained the constitutionality of the registration provisions of the Public Utility Holding Company Act.","start":3064.954,"stop":3085.123,"duration":20.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you this, what do you say to the suggestion that the passage of time and the actual experience of what was decreed in the order of -- of dissolution or the extermination of chain, the actual experience?","start":3085.123,"stop":3102.692,"duration":17.57},{"text":"Nothing happened except but that which was abstractly assumed turned out not to be so as a matter of experience.","start":3102.692,"stop":3109.546,"duration":6.85},{"text":"I'm thinking out to the exact words running through my head.","start":3109.546,"stop":3112.376,"duration":2.83},{"text":"This Court has sustained the constitutionality of rates, the famous (Inaudible) case said, “Well, we sustained it on what we know now to get experience on that come in and we'll change it.”","start":3112.376,"stop":3125.481,"duration":13.11},{"text":"Just in other words, experience versus forecast, is there anything like that in this case?","start":3125.481,"stop":3130.6,"duration":5.12}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't believe that there is in this case.","start":3130.6,"stop":3133.281,"duration":2.68},{"text":"I don't believe there's any indication that there's been a change of any conditions or circumstances --","start":3133.281,"stop":3137.924,"duration":4.64}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3137.924,"stop":3138.087,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"-- which would --","start":3138.087,"stop":3138.291,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- I think it was -- made from some specific -- gave us some specific data.","start":3138.291,"stop":3144.087,"duration":5.8}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Not of the data which Mr. Ainsworth gave this Court or as -- or the Commission has submitted in the offer of proof found at the (Inaudible) of the record.","start":3144.087,"stop":3152.984,"duration":8.9},{"text":"We contend shows a change of condition which would be the basis for the modification of -- of the prior order.","start":3152.984,"stop":3158.064,"duration":5.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, before the qualification, was there change of condition in the sense that now was established that which previously had to be nearly speculated or guessed at or an expert judgment?","start":3158.064,"stop":3168.897,"duration":10.83}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I think would have --","start":3168.897,"stop":3169.486,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What if they -- what if in a well-known phrase of an earlier opinion in this Court, it's an appeal from judgment by speculation to judgment by experience, anything like that?","start":3169.486,"stop":3179.113,"duration":9.63}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"I think what it amounts to, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, is this.","start":3179.113,"stop":3182.443,"duration":3.33},{"text":"There's some additional evidence which they should have produced at the early hearing.","start":3182.443,"stop":3187.554,"duration":5.11},{"text":"In other --","start":3187.554,"stop":3187.65,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What if they should?","start":3187.65,"stop":3188.182,"duration":0.53},{"text":"They are two different from my point of view.","start":3188.182,"stop":3189.857,"duration":1.68},{"text":"They are two totally different parties.","start":3189.857,"stop":3191.919,"duration":2.06},{"text":"The Commission is one thing and the -- and the utility is another as the counsel for the -- the Committee for the utility indicated.","start":3191.919,"stop":3201.564,"duration":9.64}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"But --","start":3201.564,"stop":3201.702,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"He couldn't be here except on the tail -- he is a tail to the Commission's kite, if there is a kite.","start":3201.702,"stop":3208.253,"duration":6.55}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"But the Commission --","start":3208.253,"stop":3209.185,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Rather an unfortunate phrase in connection with utility matters.","start":3209.185,"stop":3212.023,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"The Commission had notice of the hearing at which --","start":3212.023,"stop":3217.138,"duration":5.11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm --","start":3217.138,"stop":3217.37,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it did not appear.","start":3217.37,"stop":3217.834,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not -- I'm not suggesting they foreclose.","start":3217.834,"stop":3220.496,"duration":2.66},{"text":"All I'm saying they, in my mind has to be differentiated and I can well conceive that the Commission have a standing that the utility wouldn't.","start":3220.496,"stop":3228.797,"duration":8.3}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's certainly as obvious from reading the decision of the Fifth Circuit that that Court agreed with the Commission that there wasn't any showing of change of conditions or else there wouldn't -- that Court wouldn't have gone to the trouble of construing the sentence as it did.","start":3228.797,"stop":3245.72,"duration":16.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"From your point of view it wouldn't matter if it -- if there were change of conditions, well you think the time is for -- time therefore close, they shouldn't have come in.","start":3245.72,"stop":3254.133,"duration":8.41}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we -- we believe they have to -- both, we believe they have to show a change of condition --","start":3254.133,"stop":3258.3,"duration":4.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3258.3,"stop":3258.431,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but in any event we believe it's much too late (Voice Overlap) --","start":3258.431,"stop":3261.141,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But the other way around -- the other way around.","start":3261.141,"stop":3264.004,"duration":2.86},{"text":"If it isn't too late then one -- one has one attitude until the finding changes position.","start":3264.004,"stop":3268.737,"duration":4.73},{"text":"If therefore closed by time, I don't care about changes.","start":3268.737,"stop":3272.591,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, may it please the Court.","start":3272.591,"stop":3274.831,"duration":2.24},{"text":"It is the position of the Commission that this is a case where the Court's interest in finality of litigation need not yield to any other interest of justice.","start":3274.831,"stop":3283.584,"duration":8.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that initiative.","start":3283.584,"stop":3300.644,"duration":17.06}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 30, 1957","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13313","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 466, Securities and Exchange Commission, Petitioner, versus Louisiana Public Service Commission, et al.","start":0,"stop":9.436,"duration":9.44},{"text":"Mr. -- Mr. Meeker.","start":9.436,"stop":11.263,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":11.263,"stop":15.335,"duration":4.07},{"text":"May I call to the Court's attention at the outset that we have handed out for the Court's convenience and have also distributed to counsel a compendium of those unpublished releases of the Commission under the Holding Company Act referred to in our brief, as well as a copy of the Public Utility Holding Company Act of 1935.","start":15.335,"stop":45.751,"duration":30.42},{"text":"This case is here on certiorari to the Fifth Circuit.","start":45.751,"stop":50.837,"duration":5.09},{"text":"It involves an extraordinary situation whereby the respondent, Louisiana Public Service Commission, through the device of appealing from a 1955 order of our Commission which merely denied a petition to reopen obtained in the court below more than two years after the time for review had expired, review of a 1953 S.E.C. order entered pursuant to Section 11 (b) of the Act.","start":50.837,"stop":89.257,"duration":38.42},{"text":"The anomaly created by the court's decision below is even more obvious if the Court considers for a moment what would happen -- what would have happen if instead of having filed a petition to reopen in 1955, the respondent Louisiana Commission had filed a petition for review in an appropriate Court of Appeals.","start":89.257,"stop":119.023,"duration":29.77},{"text":"There can be no question but what if under Section 24 of the Act, that if the petition for review had been filed in 1955, the Court would have to dismiss that petition for one of jurisdiction.","start":119.023,"stop":136.807,"duration":17.78},{"text":"Now, there are two orders that are involved in this case, although there is one order which was on review before the -- initially on review before the Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit.","start":136.807,"stop":149.36,"duration":12.55},{"text":"The first of the orders which I referred to was our Commission's order of March 1953 which was entered pursuant to Section 11 (b) (1) of the Public Utility Holding Company Act referred to and included in the appendix to our brief at page 49 which directed the intervening respondent, the Middle South Utilities, Inc., and -- a registered holding company and its wholly owned subsidiary, the respondent, Louisiana Power & Light Company, to divest themselves of Louisiana powers non-electric assets pursuant to Section 11 (b) (1).","start":149.36,"stop":201.029,"duration":51.67},{"text":"I might call the Court's attention to the Commission's opinion which is found at page 103 of the transcript of record as well as the Commission's order which is found at page 127, and calling the Court's particular attention to page 128 in the latter part of the Commission's order of 1953, I would like the Court's indulgence just to read the language there, a part of the language of that order.","start":201.029,"stop":236.993,"duration":35.96},{"text":"It is ordered pursuant to Section 11 (b) (1) of the Act that Middle South and its subsidiaries, one of which is Louisiana Power, dispose their cause -- the disposition of their direct and indirect ownership in the non-electric properties owned by Arkansas, Louisiana and Mississippi in any appropriate manner not in contravention of the applicable provisions of the Act or the rules and regulations promulgated thereunder.","start":236.993,"stop":271.099,"duration":34.11},{"text":"And then in the latter --","start":271.099,"stop":271.675,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"What page is that?","start":271.675,"stop":272.311,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"-- portion --","start":272.311,"stop":272.921,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"What page is that?","start":272.921,"stop":274.046,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Page 128 of the transcript of the record.","start":274.046,"stop":276.764,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"28?","start":276.764,"stop":277.408,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"128, Your Honor.","start":277.408,"stop":278.542,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":278.542,"stop":280.155,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"And in the last paragraph, the Commission reserved jurisdiction to take further steps in the future as might be necessary and appropriate to give effects -- effect to that portion of its order.","start":280.155,"stop":297.659,"duration":17.5},{"text":"The second Commission order which is involved in this case is the order of the Commission of September 1955 which denied the Louisiana State Commission's petition to reopen the 1953 order to which I have just called the Court's attention.","start":297.659,"stop":320.902,"duration":23.24},{"text":"Now, the order in 1953 was the result of a series, a long series of hearings and proceedings under Section 11 commencing back in 1942.","start":320.902,"stop":332.925,"duration":12.02},{"text":"Suffice that to say for the purpose of this case that in 1949, among other things, the Commission acting pursuant to Section 11 (b) (1) approved the creation of the Middle South Utilities, Inc., as a holding company and reserved jurisdiction with respect to Middle South for the purpose of making determinations in the future as to the retainability by Middle South and its subsidiaries and in this case, Louisiana Power, of certain non-electric properties.","start":332.925,"stop":369.137,"duration":36.21},{"text":"Now, acting under the reservation in its order of 1949, in January 1953, the Commission, pursuant again to Section 11 (b) (1) and other sections of the Act, issued a notice -- an order to Middle South and Louisiana Power and others.","start":369.137,"stop":390.234,"duration":21.1},{"text":"In connection with that notice appearing, I should like to call to the Court' attention page 83 of the record and towards the top of the page, paragraph Number 3, the specific -- one of the specific issues enumerated in that notice of hearing whether Middle South and Louisiana should be required to take action to dispose of the gas utility assets and non-utility assets of Louisiana, and if so, what terms and conditions should be imposed in connection therewith?","start":390.234,"stop":429.616,"duration":39.38},{"text":"And I think it's rather important also to notice in connection with this order that in the last paragraph thereof, the secretary acting upon orders of the Commission is very careful to provide for a registered notice and registered mail service upon each of the Public Service Commissions involved including the respondent, Louisiana Public Service Commission.","start":429.616,"stop":457.279,"duration":27.66},{"text":"Now, in considering the facts of the case, one thing is absolutely certain and that is that the Louisiana Public Service Commission got notice of this hearing in 1953.","start":457.279,"stop":469.547,"duration":12.27},{"text":"There is no question or no dispute about that.","start":469.547,"stop":474.481,"duration":4.93},{"text":"There is also no question about the fact that the hearing which was noticed, as I've just called to the Court's attention, for February 1953 was a full hearing, an evidentiary hearing.","start":474.481,"stop":488.418,"duration":13.94},{"text":"The respondents, Louisiana Power and Middle South filed an answer which is found in full at page 84 of the record.","start":488.418,"stop":498.753,"duration":10.33},{"text":"Evidence was adduced with opportunity for cross-examination.","start":498.753,"stop":502.815,"duration":4.06}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Was the Public Service Commission a party to that proceeding?","start":502.815,"stop":506.503,"duration":3.69}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"That the Public Service Commission received notice and was entitled to come in as a person or a party if it so desired pursuant to the rules of practice of the Commission and it was specifically given notice so that it would have that opportunity if it desired.","start":506.503,"stop":525.515,"duration":19.01},{"text":"In addition to the fact that there was a direct and cross-examination, an opportunity for the same, there were arguments presented in support of Middle South's position and of Louisiana Power's position which in short was that Louisiana Power's gas properties ought to be permitted to be retained by Middle South and Louisiana as an additional integrated public utility system within the proviso to Section 11 (b) (1), known as Clause (a) to which I will refer later on in the course of my argument.","start":525.515,"stop":561.4,"duration":35.88},{"text":"But it's perfectly clear that Louisiana failed to appear, that is the Louisiana State Commission, when it had the opportunity.","start":561.4,"stop":568.955,"duration":7.56},{"text":"It's also interesting to note that no one asked for an extension, they were so concerned about these legal determinations as to which they know call -- raise as substantial issues.","start":568.955,"stop":581.829,"duration":12.87},{"text":"No one asked for an extension, neither Middle South nor Louisiana Power.","start":581.829,"stop":587.34,"duration":5.51},{"text":"Now, in March, the Commission issued its findings and opinion and order and they are found in the record, the opinion is found from pages 104 to 126 and the order is found at page 127.","start":587.34,"stop":603.325,"duration":15.99},{"text":"In short, the Commission ordered that Middle South and Louisiana Power divest themselves of all of the non-electric assets of Louisiana Power.","start":603.325,"stop":614.765,"duration":11.44},{"text":"And when I say non-electric assets, I'm referring to the gas properties and to one water property.","start":614.765,"stop":622.222,"duration":7.46},{"text":"The reason that the Commission gave in its findings and opinion was that Middle South and Louisiana Power had failed to establish that separation of the gas assets held by Louisiana Power would result in the loss of substantial economies to that additional system.","start":622.222,"stop":643.405,"duration":21.18},{"text":"And in talking about additional system, we are talking about the gas properties of Louisiana Power as required by Clause (a) of Section 11 (b) (1) so as to justify the retention of those gas assets along with the electric assets of the Middle South system.","start":643.405,"stop":665.531,"duration":22.13},{"text":"Now, very few things happened from that point on until 1954 and the only things that did happen looked toward compliance with the Commission's 1953 order which was entered after a full hearing.","start":665.531,"stop":683.777,"duration":18.25},{"text":"Not only was there no petition for rehearing filed within five days as is provided by our rules of practice, but neither Middle South nor Louisiana Power sought to challenge the Commission's substantive determinations which are raised very definitely in the yellow brief, the brief of Louisiana Power & Light Company.","start":683.777,"stop":708.017,"duration":24.24},{"text":"No one challenged the substantive determinations within the 60-day period as is provided by statute under Section 24 (a) of the Act within which a petition for review might be filed.","start":708.017,"stop":722.685,"duration":14.67},{"text":"As I have suggested, every action gave an appearance of compliance.","start":722.685,"stop":727.75,"duration":5.07},{"text":"In fact as the record will demonstrate at pages 88 and 89, Middle South and Louisiana Power asked for additional time pursuant to Section 11 (e) of the Act within which to comply, to comply with the order of 1953.","start":727.75,"stop":747.426,"duration":19.68},{"text":"And the Commission extended until March of 1955, the time within which the company's might come in and comply with the 1953 directive.","start":747.426,"stop":758.815,"duration":11.39},{"text":"Now, on November 10th, 1954, they took another step.","start":758.815,"stop":763.824,"duration":5.01},{"text":"Louisiana Power and Louisiana Gas Service Corporation, in short referred to as Louisiana Gas which is a newly organized and wholly owned subsidiary of Louisiana Power, filed an application-declaration with the Commission under the Act proposing among other things that the gas properties which the Middle South and Louisiana Power had been directed to dispose of be transferred along with the other non-electric properties to Louisiana Gas as a step looking forward -- looking toward compliance with the 1953 order.","start":763.824,"stop":807.022,"duration":43.2},{"text":"Now, finally a year and nine months after the 1953 11 (b) order to which they had been working compliance with, Louisiana Commission sends a telegram, telegrams found in the record at page 89.","start":807.022,"stop":835.574,"duration":28.55},{"text":"And the substance of the telegram and the subsequent petition and supplemental petition filed and found at the record from pages 90 to 92 was the Commission opened up the record in year 1953 proceeding.","start":835.574,"stop":856.761,"duration":21.19},{"text":"We would like to come in and present some important additional evidence.","start":856.761,"stop":865.614,"duration":8.85},{"text":"For example, I call the Court's attention to the brief on behalf of Louisiana Public Service Commission and particularly to the paragraph on page -- the two paragraphs on page 51, the -- the second and third paragraphs in which the Commission has asked to consider new evidence.","start":865.614,"stop":894.738,"duration":29.12},{"text":"Now, the Commission asked for an offer of proof and at the request of the Louisiana Commission, extended the time for its filing.","start":894.738,"stop":907.533,"duration":12.79},{"text":"The offer of proof was received.","start":907.533,"stop":910.416,"duration":2.88},{"text":"It is found in the transcript of record, commencing on page 1 and at page 5 thereof in the offer of proof, the Louisiana Commission sets forth the general reasons on which it bases its request for reopening.","start":910.416,"stop":936.403,"duration":25.99},{"text":"Briefs were submitted and oral argument was had.","start":936.403,"stop":940.794,"duration":4.39},{"text":"And subsequently in September, the Commission came out with an opinion and order.","start":940.794,"stop":949.243,"duration":8.45},{"text":"The opinion is found commencing at the record at 129 and the order at the record 133 and denied the petition for reopening on the ground that there was no basis for reopening the proceedings in its opinion.","start":949.243,"stop":968.281,"duration":19.04},{"text":"Now, in its opinion --","start":968.281,"stop":970.906,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"In the offer of proof, did they -- did they offer to introduce new testimony, new evidence?","start":970.906,"stop":979.728,"duration":8.82}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"In the offer of proof, they offered to introduce evidence with respect to the operations of the companies in 1954, evidence as to the cost of those operations and the relative cost and perhaps losses which would occur if divestment were to be carried through and they had to comply but those were based in 1954.","start":979.728,"stop":1007.691,"duration":27.96},{"text":"And as we point out in our reply brief just filed today, the -- the figures which they offer in connection with their offer of proof are in effect new data.","start":1007.691,"stop":1028.767,"duration":21.08},{"text":"They are based on new year's earnings.","start":1028.767,"stop":1031.127,"duration":2.36},{"text":"In fact in 1952, the Commission was considering figures which were before it on the basis of the operations in 1952.Here, they come in now two years later and they want to give new information or new data based on operations for the year-end in 1954.","start":1031.127,"stop":1061.092,"duration":29.97},{"text":"Now, the Louisiana Commission filed its petition for review in the court below, requesting a review of the Commission's denial of its petition to reopen and also requesting a review of the Commission's order of March 1953, the divestment order.","start":1061.092,"stop":1081.664,"duration":20.57},{"text":"We filed a motion to dismiss, the petition on the ground that in essence it was an attempt to appeal from an order as to which the time for appeal had long since expired.","start":1081.664,"stop":1095.63,"duration":13.97},{"text":"The court below found first that the Commission's order of 1955, denying the petition to reopen was reviewable and set it aside.","start":1095.63,"stop":1107.932,"duration":12.3},{"text":"It held that the S.E.C., the Commission had in effect misinterpreted the -- in the 1953 proceeding Clause (a) of Section 11 (b) (1) in legal determinations made in that proceeding in connection with the retainability by Louisiana Power of its non-electric properties and it remanded the matter to us for consideration in light of own its construction of Clause (a) of Section 11 (b) (1).","start":1107.932,"stop":1140.504,"duration":32.57},{"text":"Now, we think the court below was wrong, both on the procedural point and the substantive issue.","start":1140.504,"stop":1148.873,"duration":8.37},{"text":"The one thing I would like to say, Mr. Chief Justice, to you before proceeding to my argument is that I think upon examination of the offer of proof, the petition and the supplemental petition, the Court will readily see that there was no allegation in any of those documents of a change in conditions.","start":1148.873,"stop":1172.9,"duration":24.03},{"text":"And I think that as we will try to contend to demonstrate to the Court that is an important aspect of what has been referred to in this case as the procedural phase of it.","start":1172.9,"stop":1186.066,"duration":13.17}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as part of the procedural phrase even assuming that the order appealed from was an appealable one, then --","start":1186.066,"stop":1194.802,"duration":8.74}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"We would still contend that it was not within the scope of -- proper scope of review of an order of an administrative agency such as ours.","start":1194.802,"stop":1204.291,"duration":9.49}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"In the other aspect of the procedural question is whether or not you can have after the time appealable has expired and appeal through the medium of a motion to vacate.","start":1204.291,"stop":1216.436,"duration":12.14}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the most serious and shocking aspect of the case as far as we are concerned, Mr. Justice Whittaker.","start":1216.436,"stop":1225.739,"duration":9.3},{"text":"Now, we contend first of all, may it please the Court, that the court below committed error in permitting this 1955 attack upon a final and binding 1953 directive of our Commission.","start":1225.739,"stop":1242.079,"duration":16.34},{"text":"In so doing, the Court relied on the last two sentences of Section 11 (b).","start":1242.079,"stop":1248.853,"duration":6.77},{"text":"And if the Court will indulge me once again, I should like to examine for the Court the last two sentences of 11 (b) because we think the court below was wrong.","start":1248.853,"stop":1266.904,"duration":18.05},{"text":"Those sentences are found on page 50 of our brief, the appendix there to our brief.","start":1266.904,"stop":1273.724,"duration":6.82},{"text":"Now, it is interesting to know in going through the legislative history of this particular part of 11 (b) that nobody seems to know how these last two sentences got into the Public Utility Holding Company Act.","start":1273.724,"stop":1289.974,"duration":16.25},{"text":"There is no legislative history to guide us.We believe though that the reason for their inclusion becomes apparent on a sentence by sentence examination of those last two sentences of 11 (b).","start":1289.974,"stop":1306.763,"duration":16.79},{"text":"Taking the last sentence first, it reads, \"Any order made under this subsection shall be subject to judicial review as provided in Section 24.\"","start":1306.763,"stop":1319.644,"duration":12.88},{"text":"Now, that merely repeats -- that merely repeats the provision for appeal as contained in Section 24.","start":1319.644,"stop":1329.613,"duration":9.97},{"text":"And before I pass the legislative history, I would like to interrupt the train just a moment to point out as I neglected to do that the last two sentences were apparently added in the conference on the legislation and that may explain the reason why they're having been added at the last moment, there is no explanation in writing for them.","start":1329.613,"stop":1353.823,"duration":24.21},{"text":"But the last sentences I have indicated merely indicates that -- that Section 24 is applicable in an 11 (b) situation.","start":1353.823,"stop":1366.229,"duration":12.41},{"text":"Now, presumably an order under 11 (b) would be reviewable in the absence of this last sentence, of the last paragraph of 11 (b).I think this shows in effect that Congress was concerned.","start":1366.229,"stop":1381.491,"duration":15.26},{"text":"They were concerned lest one of these most important orders and I believe the Louisiana Power Company has referred to an order under this Section as the death sentence for which they seek commutation.","start":1381.491,"stop":1396.369,"duration":14.88},{"text":"It is that type of important order that is involved here and it is an order of unusual nature in the sense that it looks toward future compliance.","start":1396.369,"stop":1409.867,"duration":13.5},{"text":"The legislative history indicates that there was some discussion about the fact that the actual compliance with this order comes much later and the history of the proceedings under Section 11 (b) confirmed the wisdom of that legislative prophecy.","start":1409.867,"stop":1429.272,"duration":19.4},{"text":"And I think also that the lawyers who were the draftsmen here were properly concerned perhaps that maybe in view of the fact that this type of 11 (b) order looked towards the future was in effect a directive to the systems to comply at some future date to come in with a plan which would comply with the standards of 11 (b), that there was a fear on the part of the lawyer-legislators that this might be attacked as an interlocutory order from which there was no appeal.","start":1429.272,"stop":1461.536,"duration":32.26},{"text":"And it was such an important order I think that Congress and we can at best speculate but I think it is logical so to do that Congress felt that there ought to be a specific right of appeal from this type of order.","start":1461.536,"stop":1478.31,"duration":16.77},{"text":"Now, looking at the first sentence, if I may refer now to that, the Commission may by order revoke or modify any order previously made under this subsection if after notice an opportunity for hearing it finds that the conditions upon which the order was predicated do not exist.","start":1478.31,"stop":1504.779,"duration":26.47},{"text":"Now, we believe that this language was inserted because Congress was concerned that perhaps an order would be issued under 11 (b) based upon a set of particular conditions existing at a particular time which looked forward to compliance at a later date.","start":1504.779,"stop":1527.054,"duration":22.28},{"text":"And that in the intervening period from the date of the 11 (b) order and the future time at which compliance might be affected, there could be a change of conditions and this being such an important order, there ought to be an opportunity for the parties to come in and to seek a modification or revocation thereof if the conditions had changed so that perhaps the order issued earlier was no longer appropriate for the new conditions.","start":1527.054,"stop":1558.222,"duration":31.17},{"text":"Now, it seems to us that the insertion of this provision for this purpose makes awfully good sense.","start":1558.222,"stop":1571.7,"duration":13.48},{"text":"We don't believe that Congress had in mind as the Court suggest below that this language, this first sentence was to be used to come in for reopening almost at any time after a final order under 11 (b) had been entered.","start":1571.7,"stop":1591.748,"duration":20.05},{"text":"We don't believe that the Congress have that in mind because we are also mindful that the first sentence of 11 (b) on page 49 of our brief says, \"It shall be the duty of the Commission as soon as practicable after January 1, 1938.\"","start":1591.748,"stop":1615.545,"duration":23.8},{"text":"We think that the Congress had in mind that this Section ought to -- or that a compliance with this Section ought to be achieved as soon as possible.","start":1615.545,"stop":1628.445,"duration":12.9},{"text":"And such a determination or resolution it seems to us to be completely inconsistent with the concept that this first sentence opens the door for reopening such a long and protracted proceeding almost at any time at will as long as you make a allegation in effect that the record before the Commission was not complete.","start":1628.445,"stop":1652.516,"duration":24.07},{"text":"And I think perhaps that it would be well to credit to the legislators, perhaps, this concern and that is that certainly without the specific statutory authorization given to the Commission, it's doubtful, extremely doubtful under existing precedence whether it would have had the power or would have the power to reconsider such an order particularly when that order had been before a court for review.","start":1652.516,"stop":1685.591,"duration":33.07},{"text":"Thus, we think that these sentences have meanings which are contrary to the interpretations given to them by the court below.","start":1685.591,"stop":1693.849,"duration":8.26},{"text":"As to the first sentence, the Commission has consistently interpreted to permit modification or revocation of 11 (b) orders only in the light of change in circumstances which had occurred since the original order under 11 (b) was entered.","start":1693.849,"stop":1713.508,"duration":19.66},{"text":"And we have collected at page 18 of our brief that those line of cases were Commission decisions.","start":1713.508,"stop":1720.644,"duration":7.14},{"text":"Now, as to the second sentence, the Commission contends that it means that 11 (b) orders are directly reviewable pursuant to Section 24 (a) of the Act which is found in the appendix to our brief, in which provides that a petition for review must be filed within 60 days.","start":1720.644,"stop":1743.011,"duration":22.37},{"text":"Once 60 days has elapsed, it is the Commission's position -- if 60 days have gone by without the filing of a petition for review, we contend the order, the 11 (b) order is no longer subject to challenge by an attack upon the conditions found to have existed when the order was entered.","start":1743.011,"stop":1769.421,"duration":26.41},{"text":"Now, we believe also that the court below erred in holding -- in holding that Section 11 (b) authorizes the reopening of a concluded proceeding without a showing of change in circumstance.","start":1769.421,"stop":1787.963,"duration":18.54},{"text":"Now, let's see what the Court did to reach this interpretation.","start":1787.963,"stop":1793.538,"duration":5.58},{"text":"The Court construed the first sentence, which we have just reviewed, to permit a modification where it can be shown that the conditions on which the order was predicated were not truly the actual condition or in other words in the Court's own language found at the record 138 that modification might be based on the facts as they existed of the time of the order which is to be modified.","start":1793.538,"stop":1824.247,"duration":30.71},{"text":"Now, this is -- interpretation in our opinion is nothing but an open invitation to anyone in an 11 (b) proceeding who thinks he might have made a better case at some later date to come along and file a petition for rehearing.","start":1824.247,"stop":1842.512,"duration":18.26},{"text":"And we think that if this Court agrees with us in our construction that it ought -- just plain reverse and go no further with any of the issues in the case.","start":1842.512,"stop":1852.959,"duration":10.45},{"text":"To put it in another way, if this decision below is allowed to stand, all someone has to do who has rights in such a proceeding is to make a mere allegation that data in the original record before our Commission is incomplete and this decision will open the door.","start":1852.959,"stop":1876.455,"duration":23.5},{"text":"This type of reopening is rare indeed in the life of an administrative agency.","start":1876.455,"stop":1885.133,"duration":8.68},{"text":"It is even rarer when the court below requires the administrative agency to reconsider its decision made in another -- in an earlier proceeding as to which it has issued a final order back in 1953.","start":1885.133,"stop":1902.238,"duration":17.11},{"text":"We say that this result reached by the court below could only be reached if the statutory language is so clear that it precludes any other interpretation.","start":1902.238,"stop":1914.774,"duration":12.54},{"text":"And frankly, it is our position that the language of the first sentence doesn't compel any such construction as placed upon it by the court below.","start":1914.774,"stop":1924.275,"duration":9.5},{"text":"It is contrary to the congressional intent.","start":1924.275,"stop":1928.051,"duration":3.78},{"text":"We believe that in putting in this sentence, the Congress was mindful of its own admission -- admonition in 11 (b) to obtain compliance as soon as practicable.","start":1928.051,"stop":1940.239,"duration":12.19}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Could I ask you just to make sure I understand.","start":1940.239,"stop":1942.562,"duration":2.32},{"text":"Your view of this kind of a reopening order is that it is not appealable --","start":1942.562,"stop":1948.597,"duration":6.04}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":1948.597,"stop":1948.893,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and this last section only refers to the basic order, the last sentence, where (Voice Overlap) --","start":1948.893,"stop":1953.239,"duration":4.35}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":1953.239,"stop":1953.428,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- basic orders, is that it?","start":1953.428,"stop":1954.591,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":1954.591,"stop":1959.747,"duration":5.16},{"text":"If this Court agrees with the Commission's interpretation --","start":1959.747,"stop":1962.608,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask, Mr. Meeker, do you take --","start":1962.608,"stop":1964.263,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Mr. Justice.","start":1964.263,"stop":1965.198,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you take the position that the reopening order is not under any circumstances reviewable?","start":1965.198,"stop":1971.646,"duration":6.45}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we take the position that the petition for reopening under these circumstances is wholly discretionary with the Commission and that there might be a situation where -- in an extreme situation where you could perhaps show an abuse of such discretion but certainly that's not in this case.","start":1971.646,"stop":1990.867,"duration":19.22}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean an abuse to the point of an arbitrary denial of the reopening?","start":1990.867,"stop":1995.414,"duration":4.55}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, perhaps if there was a showing of fraud on the agency and the agency just refused to pay any attention to it, I would consider that a real abuse of discretion.","start":1995.414,"stop":2007.776,"duration":12.36},{"text":"But there is certainly none of that here as the --","start":2007.776,"stop":2010.544,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, apart from this case.","start":2010.544,"stop":2012.487,"duration":1.94},{"text":"I'm just wondering whether you met, and recognizes any circumstances.","start":2012.487,"stop":2018.114,"duration":5.63}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, may I say this, Mr. Justice Brennan, that it seems to me from reviewing the cases they have pretty consistently held that as far as the petition for rehearing is concerned before an administrative agency, it is a matter wholly within the discretion of the agency.","start":2018.114,"stop":2035.752,"duration":17.64},{"text":"I understand that there was a case many years ago involving the I.C.C. which held to the contrary, the Atchison case.","start":2035.752,"stop":2043.471,"duration":7.72},{"text":"But subsequently, in I.C.C. versus Jersey City, this Court very clearly restricted the decision in that case to the facts of that case.","start":2043.471,"stop":2054.032,"duration":10.56},{"text":"And in direct answer to your question, I would say we contend that a petition for rehearing is wholly in the discretion of the administrative agency, although I would not eliminate the possibility of an extreme situation where the agency acted manifestly with arbitrariness in complete disregard of some patent fact that it ought to construe.","start":2054.032,"stop":2082.148,"duration":28.12},{"text":"As I was about to say if this Court agrees with the Commission's interpretation of the first sentence, we submit that that's as far as this Honorable Court need to go and it should promptly reverse the decision below.","start":2082.148,"stop":2099.036,"duration":16.89},{"text":"Now, the interpretation by the court below of the second sentence is in our opinion clearly inconsistent with the review provisions of Section 24 (a) and the prevailing precedence.","start":2099.036,"stop":2113.766,"duration":14.73},{"text":"Again, may I call your attention to the second sentence, \"Any order made under this subsection shall be subject to judicial review as provided in Section 24.\"","start":2113.766,"stop":2134.465,"duration":20.7},{"text":"Now, what did the Court hold below with respect to this sentence?","start":2134.465,"stop":2138.545,"duration":4.08},{"text":"It held first of all that it could review an S.E.C. order denying a petition to reopen.","start":2138.545,"stop":2147.274,"duration":8.73},{"text":"In the second instance, it held that it could require this Commission to consider matters which could have been but which were not presented in the full hearing in 1953.","start":2147.274,"stop":2159.253,"duration":11.98},{"text":"And thirdly, it held that it could review at the same time legal determinations made by our Commission in connection with the 1953 proceeding.","start":2159.253,"stop":2171.366,"duration":12.11},{"text":"Now, this interpretation runs completely counter to the prevailing general rule that in the interest of the end of litigation, a failure to file a timely petition for review jurisdictionally precludes appellate review.","start":2171.366,"stop":2190.484,"duration":19.12},{"text":"As I have suggested earlier, the acceptance of this decision below in our view creates a real absurdity, to wit by filing a petition for rehearing, the Louisiana Commission can now obtain a full review in the Court of Appeals of the order denying the petition for reopening as well as the 1953 order, whereas if the same Commission had filed a petition for review on the same date in an appropriate Court of Appeals, it would have to be dismissed.","start":2190.484,"stop":2223.438,"duration":32.95},{"text":"Now, even assuming for the sake of argument that the denial of an application for modification is appealable, we believe the Court's interpretation of the last sentence was an error, both as to the availability of judicial review and the scope of judicial review.","start":2223.438,"stop":2247.617,"duration":24.18},{"text":"Admittedly, orders under Section 11 (b) which actually revoke or modify previous orders are reviewable.","start":2247.617,"stop":2257.49,"duration":9.87},{"text":"That we concede.","start":2257.49,"stop":2259.369,"duration":1.88},{"text":"But the last sentence of 11 (b) is interpreted by the court below as making the denial of a request to reopen expressly reviewable, while the words \"any order under this subsection\" as are used therein are there.","start":2259.369,"stop":2279.477,"duration":20.11},{"text":"We submit the only orders mentioned in this Section are these.","start":2279.477,"stop":2285.095,"duration":5.62},{"text":"First, orders directing that certain action be taken either integration or simplification.","start":2285.095,"stop":2292.671,"duration":7.58},{"text":"And second, that orders revoking or modifying such original orders.","start":2292.671,"stop":2299.454,"duration":6.78},{"text":"There's absolutely no mentioned in this Section of orders denying a petition for reopening.","start":2299.454,"stop":2306.575,"duration":7.12},{"text":"Certainly, action taken by the Commission which takes the form of an order and which is not required by the Act to be affected by order is not normally reviewable.","start":2306.575,"stop":2320.874,"duration":14.3},{"text":"For example, it has been held in a Court of Appeals decision, Eastern Utilities Associates versus S.E.C. in 162 F.2d, that an order of the Commission setting 11 (b) proceeding down for a hearing is not reviewable.","start":2320.874,"stop":2339.454,"duration":18.58},{"text":"Now, even assuming once again that under certain circumstances there may be a review of an order denying revocation or modification after hearing.","start":2339.454,"stop":2351.544,"duration":12.09},{"text":"We contend that such a review would nevertheless be unavailable under this second sentence from the denial of a petition to reopen without hearing to the extent that the petition is based on facts which existed at the time of the original order.","start":2351.544,"stop":2372.481,"duration":20.94},{"text":"Thus, even if the first sentence were construed to authorize the Commission, the S.E.C. to revoke or modify a prior order upon a finding as the court below suggest that conditions upon which it was predicated did not truly exist at the time of the entry of the original 11 (b) order, it does not follow that such denial would be reviewed.","start":2372.481,"stop":2401.579,"duration":29.1},{"text":"It's no different in our view from any other petition for rehearing.","start":2401.579,"stop":2406.592,"duration":5.01},{"text":"There seems to be no reason in our opinion why the denial of such petition in essence only a petition for rehearing should be anymore subject to review than the denial of any other petition for rehearing, the normal basis for which that some falls in the record.","start":2406.592,"stop":2426.133,"duration":19.54},{"text":"It is fairly well set of law the denial of the petition for rehearing is wholly discretionary.","start":2426.133,"stop":2433.51,"duration":7.38},{"text":"Certainly, it is clear in the law that a party, after the time for appeal has expired, may not reinvest himself with the right of appeal by filing a petition for rehearing.","start":2433.51,"stop":2448.109,"duration":14.6},{"text":"I call to the Court's attention, Conboy versus First National Bank of Jersey City in 203 U.S.","start":2448.109,"stop":2456.325,"duration":8.22}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Where, when you look at it, is a proceeding for a new trial based on newly discovered evidence?","start":2456.325,"stop":2464.476,"duration":8.15},{"text":"Does that make any difference to your view?","start":2464.476,"stop":2468.154,"duration":3.68}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if it's a proceeding or a new trial on newly discovered evidence, assume you would get into the question of the term of the Court and whatnot which may not be issue -- an issue in the federal court.But in our view under this Act, just new evidence alone is not sufficient to be a basis for the reviewability of such -- what we consider to be a wholly discretionary order.","start":2468.154,"stop":2500.911,"duration":32.76}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"We don't have such a procedure known as a motion for new trial before the S.E.C. anyway, did he?","start":2500.911,"stop":2507.2,"duration":6.29}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we have a procedure which would enable the respondents here to come in for a rehearing within five days --","start":2507.2,"stop":2513.866,"duration":6.67}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2513.866,"stop":2514.434,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"-- under our rules of practice but not one that analogous to what Mr. Justice Harlan has suggested.","start":2514.434,"stop":2523.858,"duration":9.42}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you take the position that there were no facts alleged here showing that the conditions on this order was predicated, it didn't exist?","start":2523.858,"stop":2535.544,"duration":11.69}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"We take the position that there was --","start":2535.544,"stop":2537.543,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's one of your position (Voice Overlap) --","start":2537.543,"stop":2538.875,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly that there was no allegation here or indication of a change in the circumstances or facts and we take that position on the basis of what the Louisiana Commission filed with our Commission and what -- what is included from the transcript of record.","start":2538.875,"stop":2555.385,"duration":16.51}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"They take the position that it's only after allege and show is that some of the findings you made before were not true, is it not?","start":2555.385,"stop":2566.814,"duration":11.43}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's -- that's correct and if that is so --","start":2566.814,"stop":2569.772,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Therefore, they do not exist and they have a right to try those facts over?","start":2569.772,"stop":2573.684,"duration":3.91}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"We take the position on the contrary, if Your Honor pleases, that it's the plain sense of -- of this provision read in light of the entire Act and the purpose of 11 (b) that this language was put in there to enable someone who was faced with such a change of conditions that made the original 11 (b) order almost non-compliable, where he could come in and seek a modification or revocation.","start":2573.684,"stop":2602.237,"duration":28.55},{"text":"But just to -- to come in and challenge the truth to the facts as they existed before, we don't believe that this goes that far.","start":2602.237,"stop":2609.745,"duration":7.51}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose they had made allegation that there were new and changed conditions, something like Justice Harlan and Justice -- and a nature of new facts and circumstances have been revealed and never been tried out.","start":2609.745,"stop":2626.023,"duration":16.28},{"text":"The fact is just completely new and you tried it out, you gave them a try and you have to reach the question here as to whether they had done that, the motion to be appealable?","start":2626.023,"stop":2635.729,"duration":9.71}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"We don't have to reach that question here.","start":2635.729,"stop":2638.184,"duration":2.46},{"text":"If they had tried it out under the language of the statute, which provides for a notice, an opportunity for hearing on the question of modification or revocation and they had a full evidentiary hearing, which was not held here on that question, then I think we have a different case.","start":2638.184,"stop":2655.502,"duration":17.32}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You say that in affect they're trying to get a new trial and this doesn't allow them?","start":2655.502,"stop":2659.954,"duration":4.45}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"They're -- they are -- they --","start":2659.954,"stop":2661.442,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Of -- of the issues that were tried there?","start":2661.442,"stop":2663.762,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"Back in 1953?","start":2663.762,"stop":2664.694,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2664.694,"stop":2676.833,"duration":12.14}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas G. Meeker","textObjs":[{"text":"As I have indicated to the Court, we consider this no different from any other petition for rehearing.","start":2676.833,"stop":2686.339,"duration":9.51},{"text":"And as we believe it, well established in the law, there seems to be no reason why this is not a matter completely within the discretion of the Commission.","start":2686.339,"stop":2697.302,"duration":10.96},{"text":"Now, at page 138 of the record in its decision, the court below said, \"Its review was not circumscribed by the rules applying to review of discretionary acts.\"","start":2697.302,"stop":2711.478,"duration":14.18},{"text":"Now, we contend that that is error.","start":2711.478,"stop":2714.282,"duration":2.8},{"text":"We contend that the last sentence of 11 (b) provides only that the Commission may revoke or modify its previous order whereas other provisions of Section 11 (b) used mandatory language.","start":2714.282,"stop":2730.007,"duration":15.72},{"text":"For example, on page 50, right above the last two sentences, the Court will note that the statute employs the use of the word \"shall\".","start":2730.007,"stop":2739.706,"duration":9.7},{"text":"It is our contention that this discretionary nature of the pertinent phrases dictates the judicial review if any should be eliminated to considerations of abuses of discretions and certainly none can be shown here, all one has to do is to examine the Commission's opinion and to examine the offer of proof which did not allege or indicate that the original factual in conclusions were incorrect.","start":2739.706,"stop":2769.791,"duration":30.09},{"text":"The abuse of discretion is not shown here and we feel that the Court went far beyond the permissible scope of review.","start":2769.791,"stop":2778.764,"duration":8.97},{"text":"Now, in the few moments that I have left here, I would like to call the Court's attention in fact that there are substantive issues.","start":2778.764,"stop":2787.999,"duration":9.23},{"text":"It's our position that you don't -- that Your Honors do not have to reach those questions here, that there is -- in the procedural aspects of this case a sufficient basis for prompt reversal of the decision of the court below.","start":2787.999,"stop":2803.28,"duration":15.28},{"text":"But I would like to mention in a very brief outline just what the substantive issues are and it maybe that I will not get to our position on them and perhaps until my rebuttal time and I hope the Court will indulge me if that would be the case.","start":2803.28,"stop":2820.003,"duration":16.72},{"text":"Calling the substantive issues which have been decided by the Commission in its 1953 proceeding and reviewed by the court below involved interpretations of what is referred to as Clause (a) of Section 11 (b) (1) found on page 49 of our brief.","start":2820.003,"stop":2846.085,"duration":26.08},{"text":"And if the Court would read from the italicized language beginning, \"Provided however that the Commission shall permit a registered holding company to continue to control one or more additional integrated public utility systems, if, after notice and opportunity for hearing, it finds that A,\" and this is Clause (a), \"Each of such additional systems cannot be operated as an independent system without the loss for substantial economies,\" and those are crucial words, \"which can be secured by the retention of control by such holding company of such system.\"","start":2846.085,"stop":2890.662,"duration":44.58},{"text":"Now, we take the position that the Court was in error in interpreting this particular clause.","start":2890.662,"stop":2897.962,"duration":7.3},{"text":"Section 11 (b) (1) of the Act requires that the operations of each registered holding company system be limited to a single integrated public utility system and to certain incidental businesses.","start":2897.962,"stop":2911.69,"duration":13.73},{"text":"Now, this proviso to 11 (b) (1), Clause (a), which I have just read, permits retention of one or more additional systems as an exception to the integration requirements if it can be shown that such retention meets the exacting requirements set forth not only in Clause (a) but in Clause (b) and (c).","start":2911.69,"stop":2934.792,"duration":23.1},{"text":"Now, these substantive issues revolve around the words loss of substantial economy.","start":2934.792,"stop":2943.094,"duration":8.3},{"text":"Now, first in construing Clause (a), the question is, should those words apply to the principal system, Middle South electric properties or only to the additional system, Louisiana gases properties -- gas property?","start":2943.094,"stop":2964.365,"duration":21.27},{"text":"And second, the question is, what is meant by the words loss of substantial economy?","start":2964.365,"stop":2971.326,"duration":6.96},{"text":"Those two questions are at issue if the Court has to reach these substantive matters.","start":2971.326,"stop":2976.973,"duration":5.65},{"text":"Now, we contend that the words loss of substantial economies refers only to the potential loss which would be incurred by the additional system, the gas properties, if it were free from the single integrated electric utility system.","start":2976.973,"stop":2998.237,"duration":21.26},{"text":"And second, we contend that loss of substantial economy means that the free utility system, the gas properties, could not stand on its own feet and operate economically if it were independent.","start":2998.237,"stop":3013.952,"duration":15.72},{"text":"To wit, we contend that Congress and we contend also and can demonstrate we believe that the legislative history supports us in this position that Congress expected, if there were to be such an additional system, that it would be able to stand on its own feet and capable of managing its own affairs.","start":3013.952,"stop":3036.717,"duration":22.76},{"text":"Unlike the last two sentences of Section -- of 11 (b) which we have discussed at length here, the legislative history here makes it clear that the draftsman intended the phrase to be interpreted as it has been interpreted consistently by the Commission.And may I again ask the Court's indulgence and suggest reference to our brief at page 40.","start":3036.717,"stop":3067.303,"duration":30.59},{"text":"But I think that at that point I will reserve my further remarks on the substantive issues until my rebuttal time.","start":3067.303,"stop":3075.332,"duration":8.03}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You may.","start":3075.332,"stop":3078.995,"duration":3.66},{"text":"Mr. Ainsworth.","start":3078.995,"stop":3081.046,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":3081.046,"stop":3095.83,"duration":14.78},{"text":"I appear here today, if the Court please, as special counsel for the Louisiana Public Service Commission.","start":3095.83,"stop":3103.678,"duration":7.85},{"text":"And I would like to sketch briefly what that Commission is before I get into the basic question of what type of allegations did we make in order to seek a revocation or modification of an S.E.C. order in a petition to the Commission.","start":3103.678,"stop":3124.25,"duration":20.57},{"text":"First of all, the Louisiana Commission is the official public utility regulatory body of that State.","start":3124.25,"stop":3133.197,"duration":8.95},{"text":"It is set up in the Constitution of that State.","start":3133.197,"stop":3136.226,"duration":3.03},{"text":"It has all necessary power and authority to regulate public utilities.","start":3136.226,"stop":3142.612,"duration":6.39},{"text":"It is composed of three elected members who are elected from geographical districts of the State of Louisiana.","start":3142.612,"stop":3150.35,"duration":7.74},{"text":"One of the Commissioners resides in the northern portion of the State in Monroe, Louisiana, another in central portion in Baton Rouge, the other in New Orleans.","start":3150.35,"stop":3159.432,"duration":9.08},{"text":"They are elected for six-year overlapping terms and they have the duty of fixing fair rates of returns for public utilities and establishing the rates that are to be paid by consumers and that is by the public.","start":3159.432,"stop":3178.057,"duration":18.63},{"text":"The Louisiana Commission's obligation and duty is therefore parallel with that of the S.E.C. It's an obligation to the public and a particular one that the consumers in this case of the services of Louisiana power.","start":3178.057,"stop":3196.068,"duration":18.01},{"text":"The S.E.C. in interpreting the Public Utility Holding Company Act feels that the divestiture of the gas properties of Louisiana Power would be proper under these circumstances.","start":3196.068,"stop":3206.696,"duration":10.63},{"text":"The Louisiana Commission feels that it would not because it offered to prove in its offer of proof that there would be a loss of substantial economies, to wit nearly a million dollars a year which would have to be paid if these two systems were separated.","start":3206.696,"stop":3225.722,"duration":19.03},{"text":"Now --","start":3225.722,"stop":3226.761,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there a reason why it didn't appear in the 1953 proceeding?","start":3226.761,"stop":3232.894,"duration":6.13}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Douglas, the reason stated in the brief, it did not -- the Louisiana Public Service Commission did not take part in the hearing, not having at that time made a study of the effects of a disposition by Louisiana such as were subsequently ordered by S.E.C.","start":3232.894,"stop":3256.841,"duration":23.95},{"text":"That's -- you'll find that in the record at page 50.","start":3256.841,"stop":3259.575,"duration":2.73},{"text":"The record at page 54, you will also find a statement that the Commission at that time had not given full consideration to the effect of such a disposition and indeed had not anticipated that the S.E.C. would order such disposition.","start":3259.575,"stop":3274.925,"duration":15.35},{"text":"And there is also in the oral argument which occurred in 1955 before the S.E.C., a statement to the effect of a clerical mishap, in getting the notice in the office, brought to the attention of the Commission.","start":3274.925,"stop":3287.655,"duration":12.73},{"text":"In any event, the Commission did not take part but it later filed its telegram, its petition and its supplemental petition.And while it is true, as counsel points out that the Fifth Circuit through a unanimous decision, written by Judge Tuttle, who was accompanied on the bench at that time by Judge Rives and Judge Jones, said that you might, in a petition for revocation, examine into the conditions which existed at the time the earlier order was issued.","start":3287.655,"stop":3327.819,"duration":40.16},{"text":"It is not correct to say as counsel has said a few moments ago that the Louisiana Commission made no allegation of change in conditions.","start":3327.819,"stop":3337.657,"duration":9.84},{"text":"I would like to read the supplemental petition, a paragraph from it by way of illustrating this.","start":3337.657,"stop":3343.303,"duration":5.65}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Where do we find that?","start":3343.303,"stop":3343.725,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"On the record, page 92 and 93.","start":3343.725,"stop":3347.665,"duration":3.94},{"text":"Subparagraph numbered 3 of the supplemental petition states that since the final hearings had in file numbers -- numbering them and the subsequent issue of order herein there have occurred substantial and important changes in the conditions and facts upon which the findings, an order of his Honorable Commission, were predicated in said proceedings of such a character as in petitioner's opinion would have lead this Honorable Commission to reach a different and contrary conclusion in these proceedings with regard to the divestiture by Louisiana Power & Light Company of its gas properties.","start":3347.665,"stop":3385.028,"duration":37.36},{"text":"Now, that is a strong allegation I suppose as the Louisiana Commission could make that there were -- that there was a change in conditions.","start":3385.028,"stop":3395.233,"duration":10.21},{"text":"I would like in a few moments to examine the offer of proof to show you in what detail the Louisiana Commission submitted those conditions and facts for the consideration of the S.E.C. and which were fully discussed and considered at the five-hour argument which occurred before that Commission here in Washington in July 1955.","start":3395.233,"stop":3417.929,"duration":22.7}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Ainsworth, was there a reason why at the initial hearing the Commission did not request, appear at least for the purpose of requesting a deferment of --","start":3417.929,"stop":3431.277,"duration":13.35}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3431.277,"stop":3431.558,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the proceeding until they had made the study?","start":3431.558,"stop":3433.75,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Brennan, I was not counsel at that time and I can only take what I find in the briefs and the statement which I personally made at the oral argument in July 1955.","start":3433.75,"stop":3443.45,"duration":9.7},{"text":"The only reason that it is stated is that the Commission did -- not having at that time made a study of the effects.","start":3443.45,"stop":3450.74,"duration":7.29},{"text":"Now, if you will look at the record, you will find that a hearing notice was issued by the S.E.C. in January 1953 for a hearing to occur three weeks subsequent to that date in February and the hearing was held on February 19th and 20th of 1953, three weeks subsequently.","start":3450.74,"stop":3471.017,"duration":20.28},{"text":"And one month later, the order on March 20th, 1953 was issued which is the basic order, which is -- which has been assailed in this particular proceeding.","start":3471.017,"stop":3480.893,"duration":9.88}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Could I go back to that petition -- supplemental petition?","start":3480.893,"stop":3484.316,"duration":3.42}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3484.316,"stop":3485.542,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Am I right in thinking that was 1955 and your original petition was filed in --","start":3485.542,"stop":3490.841,"duration":5.3}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"December of --","start":3490.841,"stop":3491.669,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- December of 1954.","start":3491.669,"stop":3493.284,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3493.284,"stop":3494.206,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And in that original petition as I read it hastily, it looks as if you were laying your ground for reopening simply on the theory that you wanted a reconsideration of the matter and that you hadn't appeared in that proceeding before and you'd like to have another encore on it.","start":3494.206,"stop":3509.768,"duration":15.56}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it -- maybe again, Mr. Justice Harlan, I -- I take the pleadings as I find them.","start":3509.768,"stop":3516.607,"duration":6.84},{"text":"I didn't write them and I'm not trying to find fault with them.","start":3516.607,"stop":3520.095,"duration":3.49},{"text":"I -- I think this supplemental petition filed at a time long before the Commission heard the argument, put our position unequivocal on the record.","start":3520.095,"stop":3528.282,"duration":8.19},{"text":"There could be no doubt where we stood then.If our December petition didn't say enough, it -- it was demonstrated by the fact that we filed a supplemental petition and they must have felt that made some support or some bolstering.","start":3528.282,"stop":3541.743,"duration":13.46}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Did the Commission enter any kind of formal appearance in the original hearing or --","start":3541.743,"stop":3545.866,"duration":4.12}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3545.866,"stop":3546.545,"duration":0.68},{"text":"No appearance whatsoever.","start":3546.545,"stop":3548.945,"duration":2.4},{"text":"And --","start":3548.945,"stop":3549.435,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you know when the Louisiana -- this Louisiana Power & Light registered, they must have registered in a place (Inaudible).","start":3549.435,"stop":3560.368,"duration":10.93}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I am not familiar with that but they were a part of the original Electric Bond and Share system which is reduced down finally to a small system of four companies in the Middle South system which owns the Louisiana Power system now.","start":3560.368,"stop":3576.587,"duration":16.22},{"text":"That Louisiana Power & Light Company operates wholly within the State of Louisiana.","start":3576.587,"stop":3581.49,"duration":4.9},{"text":"Its properties are physically situated entirely in -- in our State.","start":3581.49,"stop":3585.852,"duration":4.36}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought -- I thought the counsel said that this -- this proceeding had been going on in some form or others since 1942?","start":3585.852,"stop":3594.451,"duration":8.6}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think he's --","start":3594.451,"stop":3595.184,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"And I --","start":3595.184,"stop":3596.177,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- probably taking the original electric bond share proceeding which we had no concern whatever.","start":3596.177,"stop":3601.291,"duration":5.11},{"text":"I'm sure that the -- maybe starting it with that date.","start":3601.291,"stop":3603.927,"duration":2.64},{"text":"Actually, the S.E.C. began to function as soon as the Public Utility Holding Company Act was passed and I assume that Electric Bond and Share which is one of the large public utility holding company systems was reached rather quickly.","start":3603.927,"stop":3616.044,"duration":12.12}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3616.044,"stop":3616.213,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What's --","start":3616.213,"stop":3616.382,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- were there any proceedings before 1953 that would --","start":3616.382,"stop":3619.686,"duration":3.3}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"On the -- no, sir.","start":3619.686,"stop":3620.626,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- would have put the Commission on -- your Commission --","start":3620.626,"stop":3622.982,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3622.982,"stop":3623.3,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- on notice that -- that they were investigating this company?","start":3623.3,"stop":3626.821,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir, none whatever.","start":3626.821,"stop":3629.094,"duration":2.27},{"text":"The hearing notice of January 1953 convening a hearing three weeks hence which was held in February 19th and the 20th, two days, that's not such a protracted hearing, I don't believe or -- or a lengthily hearing, two-day hearing and an order was issued a month later, March the 20th, 1953.","start":3629.094,"stop":3648.115,"duration":19.02},{"text":"Now, in June 1953, the Louisiana Commission passed a general order to the effect that no public utility under its jurisdiction might sell or divest itself of any of its utility assets without having an order from the Louisiana Public Service Commission.","start":3648.115,"stop":3668.137,"duration":20.02},{"text":"In 1954, when the Louisiana Power filed its application-declaration jointly with Louisiana Gas, a new company set up for the purpose of taking over the gas system, it likewise filed a petition with the Louisiana Commission in November 1954.","start":3668.137,"stop":3686.118,"duration":17.98},{"text":"And it was in December 1954 that the Louisiana Commission telegraphed the S.E.C., filed its original petition and in January of 1955 when it filed its supplemental petition.","start":3686.118,"stop":3699.943,"duration":13.83},{"text":"That pretty well records the chronology.","start":3699.943,"stop":3707.738,"duration":7.79},{"text":"Now, if the Court please, going back for a moment to what I said about the Louisiana Commission's obligation being one with the public in the same sense as the Securities and Exchange Commission.","start":3707.738,"stop":3721.803,"duration":14.07},{"text":"You will find a recognition of the position of a State Commission all through this Act, I shouldn't say all through but in numerous places in the Act.","start":3721.803,"stop":3733.761,"duration":11.96},{"text":"For example in Section 8, whenever a state law requires approval of the ownership by a single company of utility assets of both in electric and gas system, the S.E.C. won't give you an order permitting that acquisition without first having approval from the state regulatory commission itself.","start":3733.761,"stop":3752.98,"duration":19.22},{"text":"Section 9 of the Act prohibits a registered holding company without S.E.C. approval from acquiring securities or utility assets.","start":3752.98,"stop":3763.214,"duration":10.23},{"text":"But removes that prohibition if you have the approval of the State Commission in the State in which those assets are situated.","start":3763.214,"stop":3770.229,"duration":7.01},{"text":"Section 21 of the Public Utility Holding Company Act states that nothing in that whole title shall affect the jurisdiction of any other Commission or agency or officer of the United States or of a State over any person, and person as defined include a corporation also, unless of course there is a conflict between the exercise of the state jurisdiction and the objectives of the Public Utility Holding Company Act.","start":3770.229,"stop":3798.286,"duration":28.06}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose this is clear because of the interest of your Commission that's why the S.E.C.gave you notice of this hearing.","start":3798.286,"stop":3805.391,"duration":7.11}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I assume that is true and I also assume that it's because the S.E.C. recognized the interest of this Commission that they invited us after we wired them in December 1954 and petitioned them in December 1954, invited us to submit an offer of proof.","start":3805.391,"stop":3822.573,"duration":17.18},{"text":"We -- we took them at their word and submitted an offer of proof, it took our staff four months to put together.","start":3822.573,"stop":3829.602,"duration":7.03},{"text":"And you'll find that offer of proof in the record beginning on page 16 and numerous pages thereafter.","start":3829.602,"stop":3835.588,"duration":5.99},{"text":"It's an involved detailed study of the accounts, both at the home office level and division level and the local level of Louisiana Power.","start":3835.588,"stop":3845.859,"duration":10.27},{"text":"The purpose of the study was to set up or project two corporations, an electric and a gas corporation and see how much more it would cost to operate two corporations where you are now operating one corporation.","start":3845.859,"stop":3857.774,"duration":11.91},{"text":"I would like to -- I see the time is about ready for adjournment.","start":3857.774,"stop":3862.689,"duration":4.91},{"text":"And if Your Honors please, I would like tomorrow to develop the offer of proof in greater detail to let Your Honors see what the circumstances were under which we came to the S.E.C.","start":3862.689,"stop":3873.296,"duration":10.61},{"text":"That the S.E.C. invited our participation at least to the extent of an offer of proof that we submitted this offer of proof and then our right to take this matter to court and ask for a judicial review is expressly provided in the statute itself, expressly provided in Section 11 (b) of the entire 33 sections of the Public Utility Holding Company Act.","start":3873.296,"stop":3898.246,"duration":24.95},{"text":"It is only in Section 11 (b) that the right of judicial review is expressly repeated.","start":3898.246,"stop":3904.594,"duration":6.35},{"text":"As counsel said, \"It need not have been placed in the Act because under Section 24 (a) you may appeal any order.","start":3904.594,"stop":3911.27,"duration":6.68},{"text":"Any person aggrieved by an order of the S.E.C. may appeal to a U.S. Court of Appeals.\"","start":3911.27,"stop":3916.073,"duration":4.8},{"text":"But here by way of recognition that Congress intended that the right of judicial review should not be taken away on a petition to revoke or modify an order earlier made where the allegations or that the conditions upon which the order was predicated did not exist specifically again repeated.","start":3916.073,"stop":3936.626,"duration":20.55},{"text":"So that to me, it leaves no doubt that we have the right of judicial review and the lower court and Judge Tuttle so held that -- I see my time is up --","start":3936.626,"stop":3947.583,"duration":10.96}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You may finish your sentence.","start":3947.583,"stop":3948.355,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Robert A. Ainsworth, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And so that Judge Tuttle in writing this opinion held that the right of judicial review was available, that the S.E.C. had treated the petition of the Louisiana Commission as a petition to revoke or modify, that it fell squarely under the provisions of the statute.","start":3948.355,"stop":3965.625,"duration":17.27},{"text":"And it was for that reason that we had a right of judicial review.","start":3965.625,"stop":3969.189,"duration":3.56},{"text":"Thank you.","start":3969.189,"stop":3971.609,"duration":2.42}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Apr  30 - 1, 1957","petitioner":"Securities and Exchange Commission","respondent":"Louisiana Public Service Commission","docket":"466","citation":"353 US 368 (1957)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/353/368","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"May 13, 1957"}